{"title_page": "Humphrey Minchin", "text_new": "'''Humphrey Minchin''' (1727\u20131796) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1778 and 1796.\n \nMinchin was the eldest son of Paul Minchin of [[Ballinakill]], King's County and his wife Henrietta Bunbury, daughter of Joseph Bunbury of Johnstown, county Carlow.  He entered [[Trinity College, Dublin]] on 11 January 1742, aged 14. He married  Clarinda Cuppidge, daughter of George Cuppidge of Dublin on 4 August 1750.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/minchin-humphrey-1727-96| title= MINCHIN, Humphrey (1727-96), of Holywell, Droxford, Hants.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1754-1790)| accessdate = 9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1774 Minchin canvassed [[Wootton Bassett (UK Parliament constituency)|Wootton Bassett]] but withdrew without becoming a candidate. He was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]] at a by-election on 11 June 1778  on the interest of [[John Spencer, 1st Earl Spencer]]. He was re-elected after a contest in [[1780 British general election|1780]]. In 1783 from April to December he was [[Clerk of the Ordnance]]. He was nominated again by the Spencer family at Okehampton in the [[1784 British general election|1784 general election]]. Although he was defeated, he petitioned and was seated on 27 April 1785.  Spencer intended giving up his interest at Okehampton at the next election and made this clear to Minchin in the autumn of 1787 allowing him to keep the seat until the dissolution.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nAt the  [[1790 British general election|1790 general election]] Minchin was returned for [[Bossiney (UK Parliament constituency)|Bossiney]], a seat that its patron [[George Edgcumbe, 1st Earl of Mount Edgcumbe|Lord Mount Edgcumbe]] put at the disposal of government supporters. Minchin had given his support to Pitt and in return constantly bothered him throughout the Parliament for an Irish peerage, which never materialized.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/minchin-humphrey-1727-96| title= MINCHIN, Humphrey (1727-96), of Holywell, Droxford, Hants.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1790-1820)| accessdate = 4 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMinchin died very suddenly on 26 March 1796 from a fit while hanging up his hat before dinner.<ref name = HOP2/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Richard Vernon (MP)|Richard Vernon]]\n | before2 = [[Alexander Wedderburn, 1st Earl of Rosslyn|Alexander Wedderburn]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]]\n | years =1778\u2013[[1784 British general election|1784]]\n | with  =  [[Richard Vernon (MP)|Richard Vernon]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[John Luxmoore (MP)|John Luxmoore]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Wiggens (MP)|Thomas Wiggens]]\n}}\n\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Luxmoore (MP)|John Luxmoore]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Wiggens (MP)|Thomas Wiggens]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]]\n | years = 1785\u2013[[1790 British general election|1790]]\n | with  =  [[George Capel-Coningsby, 5th Earl of Essex|Viscount Malden]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[John Hayes St Leger|Colonel John St Leger]]\n | after2 = [[Robert Ladbroke]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Charles Stuart (1753\u20131801)|Hon. Charles Stuart]]\n | before2 = [[Matthew Montagu, 4th Baron Rokeby|Matthew Montagu]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bossiney (UK Parliament constituency)|Bossiney]]\n | years = [[1790 British general election|1790]]\u20131796\n | with  =  [[James Archibald Stuart|Hon. James Archibald Stuart]]  \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Evelyn Pierrepont (MP)|Hon. Evelyn Pierrepont]]\n | after2 = [[James Archibald Stuart|Hon. James Archibald Stuart]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minchin, Henry}}\n[[Category:1727 births]]\n[[Category:1796 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1790\u20131796]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n", "text_old": "'''Humphrey Minchin''' (1727\u20131796) was a British politician who sat in the [[House of Commons]] between 1778 and 1796.\n \nMinchin was the eldest son of Paul Minchin of [[Ballinakill]], King\u2019s County and his wife Henrietta Bunbury, daughter of Joseph Bunbury of Johnstown, county Carlow.  He entered [[Trinity College, Dublin]] on 11 January 1742, aged 14. He married  Clarinda Cuppidge, daughter of George Cuppidge of Dublin on 4 August 1750.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/minchin-humphrey-1727-96| title= MINCHIN, Humphrey (1727-96), of Holywell, Droxford, Hants.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1754-1790)| accessdate = 9 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1774 Minchin canvassed [[Wootton Bassett (UK Parliament constituency)|Wootton Bassett]] but withdrew without becoming a candidate. He was elected [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]] at a by-election on 11 June 1778  on the interest of [[John Spencer, 1st Earl Spencer]]. He was re-elected after a contest in [[1780 British general election|1780]]. In 1783 from April to December he was [[Clerk of the Ordnance]]. He was nominated again by the Spencer family at Okehampton in the [[1784 British general election|1784 general election]]. Although he was defeated, he petitioned and was seated on 27 April 1785.  Spencer intended giving up his interest at Okehampton at the next election and made this clear to Minchin in the autumn of 1787 allowing him to keep the seat until the dissolution.<ref name = HOP/>\n\nAt the  [[1790 British general election|1790 general election]] Minchin was returned for [[Bossiney (UK Parliament constituency)|Bossiney]], a seat that its patron [[George Edgcumbe, 1st Earl of Mount Edgcumbe|Lord Mount Edgcumbe]] put at the disposal of government supporters. Minchin had given his support to Pitt and in return constantly bothered him throughout the Parliament for an Irish peerage, which never materialized.<ref name = HOP2>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1790-1820/member/minchin-humphrey-1727-96| title= MINCHIN, Humphrey (1727-96), of Holywell, Droxford, Hants.| publisher= History of Parliament Online (1790-1820)| accessdate = 4 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nMinchin died very suddenly on 26 March 1796 from a fit while hanging up his hat before dinner.<ref name = HOP2/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Richard Vernon (MP)|Richard Vernon]]\n | before2 = [[Alexander Wedderburn, 1st Earl of Rosslyn|Alexander Wedderburn]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]]\n | years =1778\u2013[[1784 British general election|1784]]\n | with  =  [[Richard Vernon (MP)|Richard Vernon]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[John Luxmoore (MP)|John Luxmoore]]\n | after2 = [[Thomas Wiggens (MP)|Thomas Wiggens]]\n}}\n\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[John Luxmoore (MP)|John Luxmoore]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Wiggens (MP)|Thomas Wiggens]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Okehampton (UK Parliament constituency)|Okehampton]]\n | years = 1785\u2013[[1790 British general election|1790]]\n | with  =  [[George Capel-Coningsby, 5th Earl of Essex|Viscount Malden]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[John Hayes St Leger|Colonel John St Leger]]\n | after2 = [[Robert Ladbroke]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Charles Stuart (1753\u20131801)|Hon. Charles Stuart]]\n | before2 = [[Matthew Montagu, 4th Baron Rokeby|Matthew Montagu]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n | title = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bossiney (UK Parliament constituency)|Bossiney]]\n | years = [[1790 British general election|1790]]\u20131796\n | with  =  [[James Archibald Stuart|Hon. James Archibald Stuart]]  \n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Evelyn Pierrepont (MP)|Hon. Evelyn Pierrepont]]\n | after2 = [[James Archibald Stuart|Hon. James Archibald Stuart]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minchin, Henry}}\n[[Category:1727 births]]\n[[Category:1796 deaths]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1774\u20131780]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1780\u20131784]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1784\u20131790]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1790\u20131796]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humphrey_Minchin"}
{"title_page": "BenQ Mobile", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| type   = [[Subsidiary]]\n| name   = BenQ Mobile\n| logo   = Benq Mobile.png\n| caption =\n| brands = [[Siemens]] (until 2006)<br>BenQ-Siemens (2006-2007)\n| logo_size = 200px\n| foundation     = 1 October 2005\n| defunct        = 30 January 2007\n| fate = Bankruptcy\n| location       = [[Munich]], Germany\n| key_people     = [[Clemens Joos]], CEO; [[Jerry Wang]], EVP and CMO; [[Alex Liou]], Head of Corporate Finance; [[Irwin Chen]], Member of the Board\n| industry       = Communications\n| products       = Mobile phones\n| assets = US$775 million\n| num_employees  = ~3,000\n| parent         = [[BenQ|BenQ Corporation]]\n| homepage       = [http://www.benqmobile.com benqmobile.com]\n}}\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens Phone Store.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens store]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF81 1.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n\n'''BenQ Mobile [[Gmbh]] & Co. [[General partnership|OHG]]''' was the mobile communications subsidiary of [[Taiwan]]ese [[BenQ|BenQ Corporation]], selling products under the '''BenQ-Siemens''' brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/tech/news/laptop/6907-benq-siemens-phone-maker-files-insolvency-protection/|title=BenQ-Siemens phone-maker files for insolvency protection|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> The group, based in [[Munich]], [[Germany]], was formed out of BenQ's acquisition of the then struggling [[Siemens AG|Siemens]] [[Siemens Mobile|Mobile]] group in 2005. The newly formed company won the most [[iF product design award]]s in 2006 and also won many design awards in Germany's [[Red Dot|red dot]] competition.<ref>https://www.benq.is/news/1141858800_34_97.html</ref> BenQ Mobile went bust later that year.\n\n==History==\nSiemens Mobile was loss-making and struggling in the market, and the division was then sold to BenQ Corporation in June 2005 to try to turn the business around. As part of the deal, [[Siemens]] would pay BenQ at least 250 million euros to get the new venture to a solid start, in return of a 2.5% stake in BenQ.<ref name=\"hexus.net\">{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/ce/news/communications/1403-siemens-seals-fate-mobile-communications-arm/|title=Siemens seals fate of its mobile communications arm|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on 1 October 2005 with the formation of BenQ Mobile, led by a German CEO, Clemens Joos, and a Taiwanese chairman, Jerry Wang. Joos had already been president of Siemens Mobile since 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2672393/new-benq--siemens-mobile-phone-company-opens.html|title=New BenQ, Siemens mobile phone company opens|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2005|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPart of the reason why BenQ was chosen by Siemens was the Taiwanese company's interest to keep German locations open - the headquarters in [[Munich]] and the manufacturing plants in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] and in [[Bocholt, Germany|Bocholt]].<ref name=\"hexus.net\"/> Other [[research and development]] and manufacturing plants were located in [[Aalborg]], [[Beijing]], [[Suzhou]], [[Ulm]] (also in Germany), [[Manaus]], [[Mexicali]], [[Taipei]] and [[Wroc\u0142aw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albawaba.com/news/benq-corporation-unveils-new-consumer-brand-benq-siemens|title=BenQ Corporation unveils new consumer brand BenQ-Siemens|author=|date=|website=Al Bawaba|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Before the acquisition BenQ was already making mobile phones \u2013 including two [[Symbian]] [[UIQ]] smartphone models and one [[Windows Mobile]] smartphone model.<ref>http://southafrica.benq.com/news/1043874000_46_294.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/31/benq_ships_p50/|title=BenQ ships P50 Wi-Fi smart phone|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=31 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens logo.svg|thumb|left|200px|Logo of BenQ-Siemens]]\nOn 17 January 2006, the first handsets under the new BenQ-Siemens brand were launched: the EF81, a slim clamshell phone similar to [[Motorola RAZR]]; the S68, a premium light and compact candybar phone targeting business users, this phone is the successor of SP65 (the S65 for some business or government who needs the protection and higher standards privacy for their staffs because the model rid off  camera function for protect taking photos of secrets papers or other in-house information of themselves ; and S88, a multimedia device with a 2-megapixel camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/17/benq_siemens_phone_launch/|title=BenQ launches first BenQ-Siemens handsets|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=17 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-launch-0601x18.htm|title=BenQ-Siemens Brand Launched - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006 the EF51 model was launched featuring music buttons on the front with a flip-down design that reveals a keypad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/02/13/benq-siemens-ef51-puts-music-front-and-center/|title=BenQ-Siemens EF51 puts music front and center|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile introduced the BenQ-Siemens P51 in March, a [[Windows Mobile 5.0]] device and the only smartphone the company would release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2657444/benq-s-new-phones-include-windows-mobile-5-0-pda.html|title=BenQ's new phones include Windows Mobile 5.0 PDA|first=Nancy|last=Gohring|date=8 March 2006|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Collapse===\nThe company ended up making huge losses, with parent BenQ losing $1 billion (\u20ac840 million) from the acquisition to September 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/6224185.stm|title=Meetings fail to save BenQ Mobile|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2006/10/04/2003330421|title=BenQ estimates a loss of US$1.1 billion on phones - Taipei Times|author=|date=|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/09/28/benq-pulls-the-plug-on-its-german-mobile-division/|title=BenQ pulls the plug on its German mobile division|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and its share price dropping by 45 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/30a5fcf6-4992-11db-84da-0000779e2340|title=Subscribe to read|author=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile only had a global 2.4% market share as of Q3 2006, demonstrating its failure to turn the business around in its first year.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/business/worldbusiness/02iht-benq.4081240.html|title=With no willing buyers, BenQ will close its doors - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In September it was announced that its factories in Mexico and Taiwan would halt production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/59a7ae06-48cf-11db-a996-0000779e2340|title=BenQ Mobile denies Germany closure|author=|date=20 September 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBenQ Mobile filed for bankruptcy in a [[Munich]] court on 29 September 2006, a day after its parent BenQ decided to stop funding the unit.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.networkworld.com/article/2307630/benq-blames-management-for--1b-loss-at-mobile-unit.html|title=BenQ blames management for $1B loss at mobile unit|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2006|website=Network World|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> This sparked a debate in Germany over whether BenQ only acquired the Siemens mobile division for its patents and intellectual property, and that it did not intend to continue manufacturing mobile phones in Germany.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-the-fall-guy-in-benq-insolvency-scandal/a-2191802|title=Siemens the Fall Guy in BenQ Insolvency Scandal - DW - 02.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The bankruptcy caused outrage in Germany over the possible thousands of job losses,<ref name=\"spiegel.de\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/ex-siemens-subsidiary-flops-benq-bankruptcy-causes-furor-a-440049.html|title=Ex-Siemens Subsidiary Flops: BenQ Bankruptcy Causes Furor|author=|date=29 September 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref> with chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] having said that Siemens is responsible for the BenQ Mobile (i.e. former Siemens Mobile) employees who are at risk.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Siemens set up a 35 million euros fund for the employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pr_cc/2006/10_oct/axx20061058_1409832.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Siemens stopped payment still owed to BenQ related to the original acquisition on 5 October<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-stops-payment-to-benq-in-taiwan/a-2195451|title=Siemens Stops Payment to BenQ in Taiwan - DW - 05.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and considered taking legal action against BenQ about the future use of the brand and patents,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/33c752f8-5339-11db-99c5-0000779e2340|title=BenQ raises rescue estimate|author=|date=4 October 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> although no claim would be made. Siemens was heavily criticised by some German politicians and labour unions for mismanagement that led to the bankruptcy under subsequent BenQ ownership.<ref name=\"spiegel.de\"/><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-chief-promises-full-explanation-of-bribery-scandal/a-2326912|title=Siemens Chief Promises Full Explanation of Bribery Scandal - DW - 25.01.2007|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A BenQ executive said that stopping funds for the Mobile subsidiary and forcing it into [[insolvency]] protection was a \"really tough decision\" and not as easy as \"just walking away\" as was reported by some media outlets.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n2,000 employees were laid off in late October 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/24/business/worldbusiness/24iht-benq.3268295.html|title=BenQ has 4th straight loss on costs for German unit - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=24 October 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nA scandal investigation was launched into Siemens's and BenQ's roles in the bankruptcy of BenQ Mobile amid allegations that financial offences were committed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/11/19/german-prosecutors-probing-benq-mobiles-bankruptcy/|title=German prosecutors probing BenQ Mobile's bankruptcy|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> As of March 2007, 13 executives, including Eric Yu, were detained in Taiwan accused of selling their shares in BenQ before the announcement knowing about the bankruptcy filing. Shares in BenQ fell 7% to its lowest level in ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/03/15/benq-faces-insider-trading-probe-as-cfo-gets-locked-up/|title=BenQ faces insider trading probe as CFO gets locked up|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee was also detained a month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.computing.co.uk/static/v3-closure|title=V3.co.uk closure|author=|date=|website=www.computing.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> At the same time Siemens was facing wide allegations in Germany of internal corruption and bribery not necessarily related to BenQ Mobile.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/a-swamp-of-bribes-siemens-forced-to-battle-internal-corruption-a-451105.html|title=A Swamp of Bribes: Siemens Forced to Battle Internal Corruption|author=|date=28 November 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref>\n\nAfter no suitable investors or buyers were found for the business, BenQ Mobile's insolvency administrator, Martin Prager, said on 2 January 2007 that the company would have to shut down.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> On 30 January the BenQ Mobile factory in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] closed. Representatives of the labour union [[IG Metall]] bid farewell to the last 165 workers with flowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306094401/http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/84493|title=heise online - Production of BenQ Mobile handsets ends in Kamp-Lintfort|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=web.Archive.org|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The demise of BenQ Mobile caused 3,000 employees to lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens|first=Jan|last=Libbenga|date=7 July 2008|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The company's assets were auctioned off in [[Hamburg]] and at [[eBay]] in March 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2007/02/26/benq_mobile_liquidation/|title=BenQ Mobile dismembered|first=Christopher|last=Williams|date=26 February 2007|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\">https://www.edn.com/electronics-news/4070317/BenQ-Siemens-to-be-auctioned</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/2442556/benq-mobile-to-be-divided-and-sold.html|title=BenQ Mobile to Be Divided and Sold|first=C. I. O.|last=Staff|date=26 February 2007|website=CIO|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and in June.\n\nThe losses of 2005 and 2006 wiped out all profits BenQ had made since 1999.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/26/taiwan-benq-insider-trading-markets-equities-lee-kun-yao.html#4a2865415634|title=Ex-BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee Cleared Of Insider Trading Charges|first=Forbes|last=staff|date=26 August 2009|website=Forbes|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===After demise===\nMartin Prager launched a 26-million-euro lawsuit against its former parent BenQ in August 2007 on top of 80 million euros already claimed. The lawsuit was partly for BenQ bonus payments promised to BenQ Mobile employees in Germany that were paid by the BenQ Mobile subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-28922620070810|title=Insolvency administrator sues BenQ for 26 mln euro|author=|date=10 August 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/08/10/bankrupt-benq-mobile-hits-parent-benq-with-third-lawsuit/|title=Bankrupt BenQ Mobile hits parent BenQ with third lawsuit|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\"/> In July 2008, Prager threatened a multi-million euro lawsuit against Siemens after claiming irregularities were found in the acquisition and that BenQ Mobile was already insolvent as early as May 2006 - a claim first reported by German newspaper ''[[Die Welt]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/Print/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens \u2022 The Register|author=|date=|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A settlement between Prager and Siemens was reached in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pressrelease/2008/corporate_communication/axx20081112.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer BenQ CEO K. Y. Lee, along with several executives including Eric Yu and Sheaffer Lee, were cleared of their insider trading, embezzlement and forgery charges in August 2009 after a two-year trial.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAfter the company closed, its former parent company, BenQ, launched five new phones (produced in Asia) under the BenQ-Siemens brand during 2007 (the license still ran for another four years). These include the A53 ([[Taiwan]] only), E52, C31, C32 and SF71 \u2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-e52-c31-07x06x12.htm|title=BenQ Siemens E52 and C31 - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/benq-siemens-sf71-joins-in-the-shiny-clamshell-fun-252065|title=BenQ Siemens SF71 Joins in the Shiny Clamshell Fun|first=Charlie|last=White|date=|website=Gizmodo|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> briefly continuing the lifespan of the BenQ-Siemens brand. In August 2007, BenQ announced that it would resume production of mobile devices using its own \"BenQ\" brand, coming with the announcements of the BenQ E72, M7 and T51 models that would initially launch in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e71.ru/news/2007-06-23-30|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c\u044e \"BenQ-Siemens\" / The last mobiles, carrying \"BenQ-Siemens\" logo - 23 \u0418\u044e\u043d\u044f 2007 - \u041a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 BenQ-Siemens E71/EL71|author=|date=|website=e71.ru|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ started making [[Android OS|Android]] devices from 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=BenQ rejoins the smartphone market with two tepid Android models |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/12/02/benq-f3-a3-android-smartphones/ |date=2 December 2013 |access-date=1 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==List of mobile phones==\n[[File:Benq.siemens.s68.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens S68]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF51.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n[[File:Benq-Siemens E71.JPG|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A38]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A58]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens AL26]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C26]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C52]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CF61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL61]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E52]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF82]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF91]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens M81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens P51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S65-DVBH]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S68]] (this was the best-selling BenQ-Siemens phone)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S81]] (''pictured'')\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S88]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SF71]] (not presented in Europe)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL80]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL91]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL98]] (not presented)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.benq.com/products/mobile BenQ Global - Communications]\n\n[[Category:Defunct mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Siemens]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Technology companies disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics brands]]\n[[Category:Bankrupt mobile phone companies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| type   = [[Subsidiary]]\n| name   = BenQ Mobile\n| logo   = Benq Mobile.png\n| caption =\n| brands = [[Siemens]] (until 2006)<br>BenQ-Siemens (2006-2007)\n| logo_size = 200px\n| foundation     = 1 October 2005\n| defunct        = 30 January 2007\n| fate = Bankruptcy\n| location       = [[Munich]], Germany\n| key_people     = [[Clemens Joos]], CEO; [[Jerry Wang]], EVP and CMO; [[Alex Liou]], Head of Corporate Finance; [[Irwin Chen]], Member of the Board\n| industry       = Communications\n| products       = Mobile phones\n| assets = US$775 million\n| num_employees  = ~3,000\n| parent         = [[BenQ|BenQ Corporation]]\n| homepage       = [http://www.benqmobile.com benqmobile.com]\n}}\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens Phone Store.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens store]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF81 1.jpg|thumbnail|BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n\n'''BenQ Mobile [[Gmbh]] & Co. [[General partnership|OHG]]''' was the mobile communications subsidiary of [[Taiwan]]ese [[BenQ|BenQ Corporation]], selling products under the '''BenQ-Siemens''' brand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/tech/news/laptop/6907-benq-siemens-phone-maker-files-insolvency-protection/|title=BenQ-Siemens phone-maker files for insolvency protection|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> The group, based in [[Munich]], [[Germany]], was formed out of BenQ's acquisition of the then struggling [[Siemens AG|Siemens]] [[Siemens Mobile|Mobile]] group in 2005. The newly formed company won the most [[iF product design award]]s in 2006 and also won many design awards in Germany's [[Red Dot|red dot]] competition.<ref>https://www.benq.is/news/1141858800_34_97.html</ref> BenQ Mobile went bust later that year.\n\n==History==\nSiemens Mobile was loss-making and struggling in the market, and the division was then sold to BenQ Corporation in June 2005 to try to turn the business around. As part of the deal, [[Siemens]] would pay BenQ at least 250 million euros to get the new venture to a solid start, in return of a 2.5% stake in BenQ.<ref name=\"hexus.net\">{{cite web|url=https://hexus.net/ce/news/communications/1403-siemens-seals-fate-mobile-communications-arm/|title=Siemens seals fate of its mobile communications arm|author=|date=|website=HEXUS|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The acquisition was completed on 1 October 2005 with the formation of BenQ Mobile, led by a German CEO, Clemens Joos, and a Taiwanese chairman, Jerry Wang. Joos had already been president of Siemens Mobile since 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2672393/new-benq--siemens-mobile-phone-company-opens.html|title=New BenQ, Siemens mobile phone company opens|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2005|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nPart of the reason why BenQ was chosen by Siemens was the Taiwanese company's interest to keep German locations open - the headquarters in [[Munich]] and the manufacturing plants in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] and in [[Bocholt, Germany|Bocholt]].<ref name=\"hexus.net\"/> Other [[research and development]] and manufacturing plants were located in [[Aalborg]], [[Beijing]], [[Suzhou]], [[Ulm]] (also in Germany), [[Manaus]], [[Mexicali]], [[Taipei]] and [[Wroc\u0142aw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.albawaba.com/news/benq-corporation-unveils-new-consumer-brand-benq-siemens|title=BenQ Corporation unveils new consumer brand BenQ-Siemens|author=|date=|website=Al Bawaba|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Before the acquisition BenQ was already making mobile phones \u2013 including two [[Symbian]] [[UIQ]] smartphone models and one [[Windows Mobile]] smartphone model.<ref>http://southafrica.benq.com/news/1043874000_46_294.html</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/31/benq_ships_p50/|title=BenQ ships P50 Wi-Fi smart phone|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=31 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens logo.svg|thumb|left|200px|Logo of BenQ-Siemens]]\nOn 17 January 2006, the first handsets under the new BenQ-Siemens brand were launched: the EF81, a slim clamshell phone similar to [[Motorola RAZR]]; the S68, a premium light and compact candybar phone targeting business users; and S88, a multimedia device with a 2-megapixel camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2006/01/17/benq_siemens_phone_launch/|title=BenQ launches first BenQ-Siemens handsets|first=Tony|last=Smith|date=17 January 2006|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-launch-0601x18.htm|title=BenQ-Siemens Brand Launched - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2006 the EF51 model was launched featuring music buttons on the front with a flip-down design that reveals a keypad.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/02/13/benq-siemens-ef51-puts-music-front-and-center/|title=BenQ-Siemens EF51 puts music front and center|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile introduced the BenQ-Siemens P51 in March, a [[Windows Mobile 5.0]] device and the only smartphone the company would release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.infoworld.com/article/2657444/benq-s-new-phones-include-windows-mobile-5-0-pda.html|title=BenQ's new phones include Windows Mobile 5.0 PDA|first=Nancy|last=Gohring|date=8 March 2006|website=InfoWorld|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Collapse===\nThe company ended up making huge losses, with parent BenQ losing $1 billion (\u20ac840 million) from the acquisition to September 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/6224185.stm|title=Meetings fail to save BenQ Mobile|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=news.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/biz/archives/2006/10/04/2003330421|title=BenQ estimates a loss of US$1.1 billion on phones - Taipei Times|author=|date=|website=www.taipeitimes.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/09/28/benq-pulls-the-plug-on-its-german-mobile-division/|title=BenQ pulls the plug on its German mobile division|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and its share price dropping by 45 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/30a5fcf6-4992-11db-84da-0000779e2340|title=Subscribe to read|author=|date=|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ Mobile only had a global 2.4% market share as of Q3 2006, demonstrating its failure to turn the business around in its first year.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/business/worldbusiness/02iht-benq.4081240.html|title=With no willing buyers, BenQ will close its doors - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=2 January 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> In September it was announced that its factories in Mexico and Taiwan would halt production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/59a7ae06-48cf-11db-a996-0000779e2340|title=BenQ Mobile denies Germany closure|author=|date=20 September 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nBenQ Mobile filed for bankruptcy in a [[Munich]] court on 29 September 2006, a day after its parent BenQ decided to stop funding the unit.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.networkworld.com/article/2307630/benq-blames-management-for--1b-loss-at-mobile-unit.html|title=BenQ blames management for $1B loss at mobile unit|first=Dan|last=Nystedt|date=3 October 2006|website=Network World|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> This sparked a debate in Germany over whether BenQ only acquired the Siemens mobile division for its patents and intellectual property, and that it did not intend to continue manufacturing mobile phones in Germany.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-the-fall-guy-in-benq-insolvency-scandal/a-2191802|title=Siemens the Fall Guy in BenQ Insolvency Scandal - DW - 02.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The bankruptcy caused outrage in Germany over the possible thousands of job losses,<ref name=\"spiegel.de\">{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/ex-siemens-subsidiary-flops-benq-bankruptcy-causes-furor-a-440049.html|title=Ex-Siemens Subsidiary Flops: BenQ Bankruptcy Causes Furor|author=|date=29 September 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref> with chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] having said that Siemens is responsible for the BenQ Mobile (i.e. former Siemens Mobile) employees who are at risk.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Siemens set up a 35 million euros fund for the employees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pr_cc/2006/10_oct/axx20061058_1409832.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> Siemens stopped payment still owed to BenQ related to the original acquisition on 5 October<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-stops-payment-to-benq-in-taiwan/a-2195451|title=Siemens Stops Payment to BenQ in Taiwan - DW - 05.10.2006|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and considered taking legal action against BenQ about the future use of the brand and patents,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/33c752f8-5339-11db-99c5-0000779e2340|title=BenQ raises rescue estimate|author=|date=4 October 2006|website=Financial Times|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> although no claim would be made. Siemens was heavily criticised by some German politicians and labour unions for mismanagement that led to the bankruptcy under subsequent BenQ ownership.<ref name=\"spiegel.de\"/><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/siemens-chief-promises-full-explanation-of-bribery-scandal/a-2326912|title=Siemens Chief Promises Full Explanation of Bribery Scandal - DW - 25.01.2007|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A BenQ executive said that stopping funds for the Mobile subsidiary and forcing it into [[insolvency]] protection was a \"really tough decision\" and not as easy as \"just walking away\" as was reported by some media outlets.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n2,000 employees were laid off in late October 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/24/business/worldbusiness/24iht-benq.3268295.html|title=BenQ has 4th straight loss on costs for German unit - Business - International Herald Tribune|author=|date=24 October 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nA scandal investigation was launched into Siemens's and BenQ's roles in the bankruptcy of BenQ Mobile amid allegations that financial offences were committed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/11/19/german-prosecutors-probing-benq-mobiles-bankruptcy/|title=German prosecutors probing BenQ Mobile's bankruptcy|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> As of March 2007, 13 executives, including Eric Yu, were detained in Taiwan accused of selling their shares in BenQ before the announcement knowing about the bankruptcy filing. Shares in BenQ fell 7% to its lowest level in ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/03/15/benq-faces-insider-trading-probe-as-cfo-gets-locked-up/|title=BenQ faces insider trading probe as CFO gets locked up|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee was also detained a month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.computing.co.uk/static/v3-closure|title=V3.co.uk closure|author=|date=|website=www.computing.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> At the same time Siemens was facing wide allegations in Germany of internal corruption and bribery not necessarily related to BenQ Mobile.<ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/a-swamp-of-bribes-siemens-forced-to-battle-internal-corruption-a-451105.html|title=A Swamp of Bribes: Siemens Forced to Battle Internal Corruption|author=|date=28 November 2006|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=Spiegel Online}}</ref>\n\nAfter no suitable investors or buyers were found for the business, BenQ Mobile's insolvency administrator, Martin Prager, said on 2 January 2007 that the company would have to shut down.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/> On 30 January the BenQ Mobile factory in [[Kamp-Lintfort]] closed. Representatives of the labour union [[IG Metall]] bid farewell to the last 165 workers with flowers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070306094401/http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/84493|title=heise online - Production of BenQ Mobile handsets ends in Kamp-Lintfort|author=|date=6 March 2007|website=web.Archive.org|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The demise of BenQ Mobile caused 3,000 employees to lose their jobs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens|first=Jan|last=Libbenga|date=7 July 2008|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> The company's assets were auctioned off in [[Hamburg]] and at [[eBay]] in March 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2007/02/26/benq_mobile_liquidation/|title=BenQ Mobile dismembered|first=Christopher|last=Williams|date=26 February 2007|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\">https://www.edn.com/electronics-news/4070317/BenQ-Siemens-to-be-auctioned</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cio.com/article/2442556/benq-mobile-to-be-divided-and-sold.html|title=BenQ Mobile to Be Divided and Sold|first=C. I. O.|last=Staff|date=26 February 2007|website=CIO|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> and in June.\n\nThe losses of 2005 and 2006 wiped out all profits BenQ had made since 1999.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/08/26/taiwan-benq-insider-trading-markets-equities-lee-kun-yao.html#4a2865415634|title=Ex-BenQ CEO K.Y. Lee Cleared Of Insider Trading Charges|first=Forbes|last=staff|date=26 August 2009|website=Forbes|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n===After demise===\nMartin Prager launched a 26-million-euro lawsuit against its former parent BenQ in August 2007 on top of 80 million euros already claimed. The lawsuit was partly for BenQ bonus payments promised to BenQ Mobile employees in Germany that were paid by the BenQ Mobile subsidiary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-28922620070810|title=Insolvency administrator sues BenQ for 26 mln euro|author=|date=10 August 2007|publisher=|access-date=28 April 2019|via=www.reuters.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/08/10/bankrupt-benq-mobile-hits-parent-benq-with-third-lawsuit/|title=Bankrupt BenQ Mobile hits parent BenQ with third lawsuit|author=|date=|website=Engadget|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"edn.com\"/> In July 2008, Prager threatened a multi-million euro lawsuit against Siemens after claiming irregularities were found in the acquisition and that BenQ Mobile was already insolvent as early as May 2006 - a claim first reported by German newspaper ''[[Die Welt]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/Print/2008/07/07/insolvency_administrator_benq_sues_siemens/|title=BenQ administrator threatens to sue Siemens \u2022 The Register|author=|date=|website=www.theregister.co.uk|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> A settlement between Prager and Siemens was reached in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.siemens.com/press/en/pressrelease/?press=/en/pressrelease/2008/corporate_communication/axx20081112.htm|title=Press Releases|author=|date=|website=www.siemens.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFormer BenQ CEO K. Y. Lee, along with several executives including Eric Yu and Sheaffer Lee, were cleared of their insider trading, embezzlement and forgery charges in August 2009 after a two-year trial.<ref name=\"auto3\"/>\n\nAfter the company closed, its former parent company, BenQ, launched five new phones (produced in Asia) under the BenQ-Siemens brand during 2007 (the license still ran for another four years). These include the A53 ([[Taiwan]] only), E52, C31, C32 and SF71 \u2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mobilegazette.com/benq-siemens-e52-c31-07x06x12.htm|title=BenQ Siemens E52 and C31 - Mobile Gazette - Mobile Phone News|author=|date=|website=www.mobilegazette.com|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/benq-siemens-sf71-joins-in-the-shiny-clamshell-fun-252065|title=BenQ Siemens SF71 Joins in the Shiny Clamshell Fun|first=Charlie|last=White|date=|website=Gizmodo|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> briefly continuing the lifespan of the BenQ-Siemens brand. In August 2007, BenQ announced that it would resume production of mobile devices using its own \"BenQ\" brand, coming with the announcements of the BenQ E72, M7 and T51 models that would initially launch in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://e71.ru/news/2007-06-23-30|title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0444\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c\u044e \"BenQ-Siemens\" / The last mobiles, carrying \"BenQ-Siemens\" logo - 23 \u0418\u044e\u043d\u044f 2007 - \u041a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 BenQ-Siemens E71/EL71|author=|date=|website=e71.ru|access-date=28 April 2019}}</ref> BenQ started making [[Android OS|Android]] devices from 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=BenQ rejoins the smartphone market with two tepid Android models |url=https://www.engadget.com/2013/12/02/benq-f3-a3-android-smartphones/ |date=2 December 2013 |access-date=1 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==List of mobile phones==\n[[File:Benq.siemens.s68.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens S68]]\n[[File:BenQ-Siemens EF51.jpg|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n[[File:Benq-Siemens E71.JPG|thumb|200px|BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A38]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens A58]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens AL26]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C26]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C52]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens C81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CF61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL61]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens CL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E52]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E61]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EL71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF71]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens E81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF82]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens EF91]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens M81]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens P51]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S65-DVBH]] (not presented)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S68]] (this was the best-selling BenQ-Siemens phone)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S81]] (''pictured'')\n* [[BenQ-Siemens S88]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SF71]] (not presented in Europe)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL80]]\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL91]] (cancelled)\n* [[BenQ-Siemens SL98]] (not presented)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.benq.com/products/mobile BenQ Global - Communications]\n\n[[Category:Defunct mobile phone manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Siemens]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2006]]\n[[Category:Technology companies disestablished in 2009]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Technology companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Consumer electronics brands]]\n[[Category:Bankrupt mobile phone companies]]\n", "name_user": "Toxicxtina", "label": "safe", "comment": "S68 history improvements and marketing positions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BenQ_Mobile"}
{"title_page": "Jim Clemente", "text_new": "{{short description|American author, FBI profiler}}\n'''James \"Jim\" T. Clemente''' (born in San Mateo, California) is an American author, former New York State prosecutor, former FBI profiler, podcast co-host and creator of the show ''[[Real Crime Profile]]'', and writer/producer on CBS' ''[[Criminal Minds]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unstructuredpod.com/130-jim-clemente-is-a-retired-fbi-profiler-and-now-criminal-minds-writer-and-producer/|title=130 - Jim Clemente is a retired FBI Profiler and now Criminal Minds writer and producer|date=2019-02-27|website=Unstructured Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://1in6.org/get-information/bristlecone/jim-clemente/|title=Male Sexual Abuse and Assault - Jim Clemente's Story|website=1in6|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/184259-who-is-jim-clemente-the-fbi-agent-in-jonbenet-ramseys-case-switched-careers|title=Jim Clemente, Former FBI Agent, Switched Careers|last=Corbett|first=Erin|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nAs a child, Clemente was a victim of sexual abuse.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/98640703/fbi-agent-for-22-years-author-and-child-abuse-expert-jim-clemente-speaks-in-christchurch|title=FBI agent for 22 years, author and child abuse expert Jim Clemente speaks in Christchurch|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> It wasn't until he became a prosecutor in New York that he came forward about the abuse and decided to take action. After contacting the FBI and NYPD's Sexual Exploitation of Children Task Force, he agreed to wear a wire and was able to gather evidence to convict his abuser, the former camp director of a [[Catholic Youth Organization]] (CYO) camp, where he attended.<ref name=\":0\" /> Following this take-down, he was recruited by the FBI where he worked as an undercover agent and a profiler in the Behavioral Analysis Unit.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== FBI ==\nClemente worked for the FBI for 22 years where he was an expert on child sexual abuse, victimization, abduction and homicide. He's also an expert in criminal behavioral profiling.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.paterno.com/expert-reports/jim-clemente.aspx#.XKJdHBOpE_U|title=Expert Reports - Jim Clemente|website=www.paterno.com|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> He worked undercover in a multi-year Wall Street investigation, worked the White Water investigation, and was part of the team that cracked the [[D.C. sniper attacks|DC Sniper]] case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bakadesuyo.com/2013/10/fbi-profiler/|title=FBI Profiler Jim Clemente Talks Serial Killers, Deception And Danger|date=2013-10-07|website=Barking Up The Wrong Tree|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\nJim's brother is [[Tim Clemente]] who also served as a special agent in the FBI.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Television ==\nClemente began working as a technical advisor and freelance writer for CBS' ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' in 2010. In 2015, he became a producer on the show where he continued to write and produce through its final season in 2019.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2428141/|title=Jim Clemente|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-04-01}} {{better source|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nClemente was a technical advisor on the television series ''[[Secrets and Lies (U.S. TV series)|Secrets and Lies]]'', ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]'', ''[[Misconduct (film)|Midconduct]]'', and ''[[Blindspot (TV series)|Blindspot]]''.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nClemente created and produced the television show ''[[Manhunt: Unabomber]]'', an 8-episode limited series released by [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]] in 2017.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Podcasts ==\nClemente is the co-host of the podcast ''[[Real Crime Profile]]'' distributed on [[Wondery]]. He also hosted the limited series podcast ''Locked Up Abroad'' which served as an audio adaptation to the [[National Geographic (TV network)|National Geographic]] television show of the same name (''Locked Up Abroad).''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discoverpods.com/four-best-podcasts-wondery-labor-day-traffic/|title=The Four Best Podcasts For That Labor Day Traffic|date=2017-09-01|website=Discover the Best Podcasts {{!}} Discover Pods|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> Jim also co-created and co-hosts the podcast Best Case Worst Case where listeners are taken behind police lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wondery.com/shows/best-case-worst-case/|title=Best Case Worst Case \u2013 Wondery \u2013 Feel The Story|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clemente, Jim}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author, FBI profiler}}\n'''James \"Jim\" T. Clemente''' (born in San Mateo, California) is an American author, former New York State prosecutor, former FBI profiler, podcast co-host and creator of the show ''[[Real Crime Profile]]'', and writer/producer on CBS' ''[[Criminal Minds]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unstructuredpod.com/130-jim-clemente-is-a-retired-fbi-profiler-and-now-criminal-minds-writer-and-producer/|title=130 - Jim Clemente is a retired FBI Profiler and now Criminal Minds writer and producer|date=2019-02-27|website=Unstructured Podcast|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://1in6.org/get-information/bristlecone/jim-clemente/|title=Male Sexual Abuse and Assault - Jim Clemente's Story|website=1in6|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/articles/184259-who-is-jim-clemente-the-fbi-agent-in-jonbenet-ramseys-case-switched-careers|title=Jim Clemente, Former FBI Agent, Switched Careers|last=Corbett|first=Erin|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nAs a child, Clemente was a victim of sexual abuse.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/crime/98640703/fbi-agent-for-22-years-author-and-child-abuse-expert-jim-clemente-speaks-in-christchurch|title=FBI agent for 22 years, author and child abuse expert Jim Clemente speaks in Christchurch|website=Stuff|language=en|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> It wasn't until he became a prosecutor in New York that he came forward about the abuse and decided to take action. After contacting the FBI and NYPD's Sexual Exploitation of Children Task Force, he agreed to wear a wire and was able to gather evidence to convict his abuser, the former camp director of a [[Catholic Youth Organization]] (CYO) camp, where he attended.<ref name=\":0\" /> Following this take-down, he was recruited by the FBI where he worked as an undercover agent and a profiler in the Behavioral Analysis Unit.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== FBI ==\nClemente worked for the FBI for 22 years where he was an expert on child sexual abuse, victimization, abduction and homicide. He's also an expert in criminal behavioral profiling.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.paterno.com/expert-reports/jim-clemente.aspx#.XKJdHBOpE_U|title=Expert Reports - Jim Clemente|website=www.paterno.com|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> He worked undercover in a multi-year Wall Street investigation, worked the White Water investigation, and was part of the team that cracked the [[D.C. sniper attacks|DC Sniper]] case.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bakadesuyo.com/2013/10/fbi-profiler/|title=FBI Profiler Jim Clemente Talks Serial Killers, Deception And Danger|date=2013-10-07|website=Barking Up The Wrong Tree|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\nJim's brother is [[Tim Clemente]] who also served as a special agent in the FBI.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Television ==\nClemente began working as a technical advisor and freelance writer for CBS' ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' in 2010. In 2015, he became a producer on the show where he continued to write and produce through its final season in 2019.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2428141/|title=Jim Clemente|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-04-01}} {{better source|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nClemente was a technical advisor on the television series ''[[Secrets and Lies (U.S. TV series)|Secrets and Lies]]'', ''[[Quantico (TV series)|Quantico]]'', ''[[Misconduct (film)|Midconduct]]'', and ''[[Blindspot (TV series)|Blindspot]]''.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nClemente created and produced the television show ''[[Manhunt: Unabomber]]'', an 8-episode limited series released by [[Discovery Channel|Discovery]] in 2017.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Podcasts ==\nClemente is the co-host of the podcast ''[[Real Crime Profile]]'' distributed on [[Wondery]]. He also hosted the limited series podcast ''Locked Up Abroad'' which served as an audio adaptation to the [[National Geographic (TV network)|National Geographic]] television show of the same name (''Locked Up Abroad).''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discoverpods.com/four-best-podcasts-wondery-labor-day-traffic/|title=The Four Best Podcasts For That Labor Day Traffic|date=2017-09-01|website=Discover the Best Podcasts {{!}} Discover Pods|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref> Jim also co-created and co-hosts the podcast Best Case Worst Case where listeners are taken behind police lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wondery.com/shows/best-case-worst-case/|title=Best Case Worst Case \u2013 Wondery \u2013 Feel The Story|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clemente, Jim}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth 