{"title_page": "Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball of Durham", "text_new": "{{short description|Annual ball in Durham, North Carolina}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name = Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball\n|logo = \n|image = \n|imagesize = \n|caption = \n|genre = [[debutante ball]]\n|date = December\n|frequency = annually \n|location = Duke Convention Center<br>[[Durham, North Carolina]]<br>United States\n|first = 1955\n|founder_name = Mrs. Thomas Davenport Wright\n|prev = \n|next = \n|participants =\n|attendance =\n|area =\n|budget =\n|patron = The Debutante Ball Society of Durham\n|organised = \n|people = \n|member =\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\nThe '''Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball of Durham''' is an annual Christmas ball held in [[Durham, North Carolina]], in the United States in late December. The ball, organized by the Debutante Ball Society of Durham, was founded in 1955 as a [[debutante ball]] for women from [[Durham County, North Carolina|Durham]] and [[Orange County, North Carolina|Orange counties]].\n\n== About ==\nIn 1955 the first Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball of Durham was established by Mrs. Thomas Davenport Wright. The Debutante Ball Society of Durham, which now hosts the ball, was established in 1961 by Davenport, Mrs. Edward McCullogh Cameron, Mrs. Charles Harris Livengood Jr, Mrs. Edward Stewart Orgain, and Mrs. William Edwards Cranford.<ref name= kat/> Debutantes are selected from prominent families of Durham, [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], and other areas in [[Orange County, North Carolina|Orange County]].<ref name= finding>{{Cite web|url=https://finding-aids.lib.unc.edu/05199/|title=Debutante Ball Society of Durham Inc. Records, 1951-2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/debutante-cotillion-and-christmas-ball-collection/oclc/757512859|title=Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball Collection.|date=February 21, 1955|via=Open WorldCat}}</ref> The ball was originally given as a benefit for the maintenance of [[Kenmore (Fredericksburg, Virginia)|Kenmore Plantation]] in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]].<ref name= kat>{{Cite web|url=http://kats-eyeview.blogspot.com/2010/01/modern-debutante.html|title=modern debutante|date=January 12, 2010|website=kats-eyeview.blogspot.com}}</ref> The [[Durham Arts Council]] later became the beneficiary of the ball.<ref name= kat/>\n\nIn the 1950s, the ball consisted of a receiving line, a garland waltz, a formal cotillion, singing of Christmas carols, and addresses by local clergymen. In later years, a sleigh ride and minuet were added, as well as the lighting of a Christmas tree.<ref name= kat/>\n\nThe ball, originally held at the National Guard Armory, takes place at the Durham Convention Center in the [[Downtown Durham Historic District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchworks.oclc.org/archivegrid/collection/data/757512859|title=Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball Collection|website=researchworks.oclc.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/shannonmedia/docs/dma17_issuu/17|title=Durham Magazine April 2017|website=Issuu}}</ref>\n\nDebutantes are announced every year in May during a [[Mother's Day]] luncheon at [[Hope Valley Historic District (Durham, North Carolina)|Hope Valley Country Club]].<ref name= aesthetic/><ref name= finding/> For the remainder of the year until the cotillion and ball, parties and other social events take place for the debutantes, including a father & daughter luncheon at Chapel Hill Country Club.<ref name= finding/><ref name= aesthetic>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aestheticimages.net/blog-post/debutante-ball-society-holds-65th-annual-cotillion-in-durham|title=Debutante Ball Society Holds 65th Annual Cotillion in Durham|first=Jeff|last=Hyde|website=Aesthetic Images Photography}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1955 establishments in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Annual events in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Balls in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christmas in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dance in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Debutante balls]]\n[[Category:History of Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Winter events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Annual ball in Durham, North Carolina}}\n{{Infobox recurring event\n|name = Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball\n|logo = \n|image = \n|imagesize = \n|caption = \n|genre = [[debutante ball]]\n|date = December\n|frequency = annually \n|location = Duke Convention Center<br>[[Durham, North Carolina]]<br>United States\n|first = 1955\n|founder_name = Mrs. Thomas Davenport Wright\n|prev = \n|next = \n|participants =\n|attendance =\n|area =\n|budget =\n|patron = The Debutante Ball Society of Durham\n|organised = \n|people = \n|member =\n|website = \n|footnotes =\n}}\nThe '''Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball of Durham''' is an annual Christmas ball held in [[Durham, North Carolina]], in the United States in late December. The ball, organized by the Debutante Ball Society of Durham, was founded in 1955 as a [[debutante ball]] for women from [[Durham County, North Carolina|Durham]] and [[Orange County, North Carolina|Orange counties]].\n\n== About ==\nIn 1955 the first Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball of Durham was established by Mrs. Thomas Davenport Wright. The Debutante Ball Society of Durham, which now hosts the ball, was established in 1961 by Davenport, Mrs. Edward McCullogh Cameron, Mrs. Charles Harris Livengood Jr, Mrs. Edward Stewart Orgain, and Mrs. William Edwards Cranford.<ref name= kat/> Debutantes are selected from prominent families of Durham, [[Chapel Hill, North Carolina|Chapel Hill]], and other areas in [[Orange County, North Carolina|Orange County]].<ref name= finding>{{Cite web|url=https://finding-aids.lib.unc.edu/05199/|title=Debutante Ball Society of Durham Inc. Records, 1951-2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/debutante-cotillion-and-christmas-ball-collection/oclc/757512859|title=Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball Collection.|date=February 21, 1955|via=Open WorldCat}}</ref> The ball was originally given as a benefit for the maintenance of [[Kenmore (Fredericksburg, Virginia)|Kenmore Plantation]] in [[Fredericksburg, Virginia]].<ref name= kat>{{Cite web|url=http://kats-eyeview.blogspot.com/2010/01/modern-debutante.html|title=modern debutante|date=January 12, 2010|website=kats-eyeview.blogspot.com}}</ref> The [[Durham Arts Council]] later became the beneficiary of the ball.<ref name= kat/>\n\nIn the 1950s, the ball consisted of a receiving line, a garland waltz, a formal cotillion, singing of Christmas carols, and addresses by local clergymen. In later years, a sleigh ride and minuet were added, as well as the lighting of a Christmas tree.<ref name= kat/>\n\nThe ball, originally held at the National Guard Armory, takes place at the Durham Convention Center in the [[Downtown Durham Historic District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://researchworks.oclc.org/archivegrid/collection/data/757512859|title=Debutante Cotillion and Christmas Ball Collection|website=researchworks.oclc.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/shannonmedia/docs/dma17_issuu/17|title=Durham Magazine April 2017|website=Issuu}}</ref>\n\nDebutantes are announced every year in May during a [[Mother's Day]] luncheon at [[Hope Valley Historic District|Hope Valley Country Club]].<ref name= aesthetic/><ref name= finding/> For the remainder of the year until the cotillion and ball, parties and other social events take place for the debutantes, including a father & daughter luncheon at Chapel Hill Country Club.<ref name= finding/><ref name= aesthetic>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aestheticimages.net/blog-post/debutante-ball-society-holds-65th-annual-cotillion-in-durham|title=Debutante Ball Society Holds 65th Annual Cotillion in Durham|first=Jeff|last=Hyde|website=Aesthetic Images Photography}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1955 establishments in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Annual events in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Balls in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christmas in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dance in North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Debutante balls]]\n[[Category:History of Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Winter events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHope Valley Historic District(link changed toHope Valley Historic District (Durham, North Carolina)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debutante_Cotillion_and_Christmas_Ball_of_Durham"}
{"title_page": "Cherry picking", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|Logical fallacy}}\n'''Cherry picking''', '''suppressing evidence''', or the '''fallacy of incomplete evidence''' is the act of pointing to individual cases or data that seem to confirm a particular position while ignoring a significant portion of related and similar cases or data that may [[Contradiction|contradict]] that position. It is a kind of [[fallacy]] of selective attention, the most common example of which is the [[confirmation bias]].<ref>[http://www.iep.utm.edu/fallacy/#SuppressedEvidence The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, \"Fallacies\", Bradley Dowden (2010)]</ref><ref>[http://www.logicallyfallacious.com/index.php/logical-fallacies/66-cherry-picking Cherry Picking]</ref> Cherry picking may be committed intentionally or unintentionally. This fallacy is a major problem in public debate.<ref>{{cite web|last= Klass|first= Gary|title= Just Plain Data Analysis: Common Statistical Fallacies in Analyses of Social Indicator Data. Department of Politics and Government, Illinois State University|website= statlit.org. ~2008|accessdate= March 25, 2014|url= http://www.statlit.org/pdf/2008KlassASA.pdf|format= PDF|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140325173711/http://www.statlit.org/pdf/2008KlassASA.pdf|archivedate= March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe term is based on the perceived process of harvesting fruit, such as [[cherry|cherries]].  The picker would be expected to only select the ripest and healthiest fruits. An observer who only sees the selected fruit may thus wrongly conclude that most, or even all, of the tree's fruit is in a likewise good condition. This can also give a false impression of the quality of the fruit (since it is only a sample and is not a [[representative sample]]). A concept sometimes confused with cherry picking is the idea of gathering only the fruit that is easy to harvest, while ignoring other fruit that is higher up on the tree and thus more difficult to obtain (see [[low-hanging fruit]]).\n\nCherry picking has a negative connotation as the practice neglects, overlooks or directly suppresses evidence that could lead to a complete picture. \n\nCherry picking can be found in many [[fallacy|logical fallacies]]. For example, the \"fallacy of [[anecdotal evidence]]\" tends to overlook large amounts of data in favor of that known personally, \"selective use of evidence\" rejects material unfavorable to an argument, while a [[false dichotomy]] picks only two options when more are available. Cherry picking can refer to the selection of data or data sets so a study or survey will give desired, predictable results which may be misleading or even completely contrary to reality.<ref name=\"Goldacre2008\">{{cite book|last=Goldacre|first=Ben|authorlink=Ben Goldacre|title=Bad Science|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gv1NQubrGNIC|year=2008|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|isbn=978-0-00-728319-4|pages=97\u201399}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAn anecdotal story about the 5th century BC atheist philosopher [[Diagoras of Melos]] says how, when shown the votive gifts of people who had supposedly escaped death by shipwreck by praying to gods, he pointed out that many people ''had'' died at sea in spite of their prayers, yet these cases were not likewise commemorated.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jennifer Michael|last=Hecht|authorlink=Jennifer Michael Hecht|title=Doubt: A History|publisher=Harper San Francisco|year=2003|chapter=Whatever Happened to Zeus and Hera?, 600 BCE-1 CE|pages=9\u201310|isbn=0-06-009795-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QJb16_AAePkC&pg=PA10}}</ref> [[Michel de Montaigne]] (1533-1592) in his [[Essays (Montaigne)|essay on prophecies]] comments on people willing to believe in the validity of supposed seers: \n{{quote|I see some who are mightily given to study and comment upon their almanacs, and produce them to us as an authority when anything has fallen out pat; and, for that matter, it is hardly possible but that these alleged authorities sometimes stumble upon a truth amongst an infinite number of lies. ... I think never the better of them for some such accidental hit. ... [N]obody records their flimflams and false prognostics, forasmuch as they are infinite and common; but if they chop upon one truth, that carries a mighty report, as being rare, incredible, and prodigious.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michel de Montaigne|title=Essays|chapter=Chapter XI--Of Prognostications|others=Translated by Charles Cotton|year=1877|orig-year=First French edition 1580|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/3600}}</ref>}}\n\n==In science==\n[[File:Temperaturanstieg-vergleich-zwischen-ausschnitt-und-gesamtverlauf.gif|thumb|320px|Cherry-picking is often used in [[denialism|science denial]] such as [[climate change denial]]. For example, by deliberately cherry picking appropriate time periods, here 1998\u20132012, an artificial \"pause\" can be created, even when there is an ongoing warming trend.<ref name=\"Hansson\">[[Sven Ove Hansson]]: ''Science denial as a form of pseudoscience''. [[Studies in History and Philosophy of Science]]. 63, 2017, pp 39\u201347, {{DOI|10.1016/j.shpsa.2017.05.002}}.</ref>]]\n\nCherry picking is one of the epistemological characteristics of [[denialism]] and widely used by different science [[Denialism|denialists]] to seemingly contradict scientific findings. For example, it is used in [[climate change denial]], denial of the negative health effects of consuming [[tobacco products]] and passive smoking and [[evolution denial]] by creationists.<ref name=\"Hansson\" />\n\n{{Quote\n| Choosing to make selective choices among competing evidence, so as to emphasize those results that support a given position, while ignoring or dismissing any findings that do not support it, is a practice known as \"cherry picking\" and is a hallmark of poor science or pseudo-science.<ref name=\"scienceornot\">[http://scienceornot.net/2012/04/03/devious-deception-in-displaying-data-cherry-picking/ \"Devious deception in displaying data: Cherry picking\"], ''Science or Not,'' April 3, 2012, retrieved 16 February 2015</ref>\n| [[Richard Somerville]], Testimony before the US House of Representatives Committee on Energy and Commerce Subcommittee on Energy and Power, March 8, 2011.\n}}\n\n{{Quote\n | Rigorous science looks at all the evidence (rather than cherry picking only favorable evidence), controls for variables as to identify what is actually working, uses blinded observations so as to minimize the effects of bias, and uses internally consistent logic.\"<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.sciencebasedmedicine.org/index.php/a-skeptic-in-oz/\n | title = A Skeptic In Oz\n | last = Novella \n | first = Steven\n | authorlink = Steven Novella\n | date = 26 April 2011\n | website = [[Science-Based Medicine (website)|Science-Based Medicine]]\n | access-date = 16 February 2015 }}\n</ref>\n | [[Steven Novella]], \"A Skeptic In Oz\", April 26, 2011\n}}\n\n==In medicine==\nIn a 2002 study, a review of previous medical data found cherry picking in tests of anti-depression medication:\n\n<blockquote>[researchers] reviewed 31 antidepressant efficacy trials to identify the primary exclusion criteria used in determining eligibility for participation. Their findings suggest that patients in current antidepressant trials represent only a minority of patients treated in routine clinical practice for depression. Excluding potential clinical trial subjects with certain profiles means that the ability to generalize the results of antidepressant efficacy trials lacks empirical support, according to the authors.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Typical Depression Patients Excluded from Drug Trials; exclusion criteria: is it 'cherry pickin'? |url= |journal=The Brown University Psychopharmacology Update |publisher=Wiley Periodicals |volume=13 |issue=5 |date=May 2002 |pages=1\u20133|issn=1068-5308}} Based on the studies:\n* {{cite journal |last1=Posternak |first1=MA |last2=Zimmerman |first2=M |last3=Keitner |first3=GI |last4=Miller |first4=IW |title=A reevaluation of the exclusion criteria used in antidepressant efficacy trials |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |date=February 2002 |volume=159 |issue=2 |pages=191\u2013200 |pmid=11823258 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.159.2.191}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Zimmerman |first1=M |last2=Mattia |first2=JI |last3=Posternak |first3=MA |title=Are subjects in pharmacological treatment trials of depression representative of patients in routine clinical practice? |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |date=March 2002 |volume=159 |issue=3 |pages=469\u201373 |pmid=11870014 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.159.3.469}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==In argumentation==\nIn argumentation, the practice of \"[[quote mining]]\" is a form of cherry picking,<ref name=\"scienceornot\" /> in which the debater selectively picks some quotes supporting a position (or exaggerating an opposing position) while ignoring those that moderate the original quote or put it into a different context. Cherry picking in debates is a large problem as the facts themselves are true but need to be put in context. Because research cannot be done live and is often untimely, cherry-picked facts or quotes usually stick in the public mainstream and, even when corrected, lead to widespread misrepresentation of groups targeted.\n\n==One-sided argument<!--'One-sided argument' redirects here-->==\nA '''one-sided argument''' (also known as '''card stacking''', '''stacking the deck''', '''ignoring the counterevidence''', '''slanting''', and '''suppressed evidence''')<ref name=stacking>{{cite web|title=One-Sidedness - The Fallacy Files|url=http://www.fallacyfiles.org/onesided.html|accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref> is an [[informal fallacy]] that occurs when only the reasons supporting a proposition are supplied, while all reasons opposing it are omitted.\n\nPhilosophy professor [[Peter Suber]] has written: \"The one-sidedness fallacy does not make an argument invalid. It may not even make the argument unsound. The fallacy consists in persuading readers, and perhaps ourselves, that we have said enough to tilt the scale of evidence and therefore enough to justify a judgment. If we have been one-sided, though, then we haven't yet said enough to justify a judgment. The arguments on the other side may be stronger than our own. We won't know until we examine them.  So the one-sidedness fallacy doesn't mean that your premises are false or irrelevant, only that they are incomplete.\"<ref name=\"Suber\">{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/courses/inflogic/onesided.htm |title=The One-Sidedness Fallacy |author=Peter Suber |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"With rational messages, you need to decide if you want to use a one-sided argument or a two-sided argument. A one-sided argument only presents the pro side of the argument, while a two-sided argument presents both sides. Which one you use will depend on which one meets your needs and the type of audience. Generally, one-sided arguments are better with audiences already favorable to your message. Two-sided arguments are best with audiences who are opposed to your argument, are better educated or have already been exposed to counter arguments.\"<ref name=\"Suber\"/>\n\n'''Card stacking''' is a [[propaganda]] technique that seeks to manipulate audience perception of an issue by emphasizing one side and repressing another.<ref>{{cite book |title=The fine art of propaganda: a study of Father Coughlin's s=Institute for Propaganda Analysis |first= |authorlink= |year=1939 |publisher=Harcourt Brace and Company |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=95\u2013101 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzVMAAAAIAAJ&q=%22card+stacking%22&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> Such emphasis may be achieved through [[media bias]] or the use of [[One-sided argument|one-sided]] testimonials, or by simply [[Censorship|censoring]] the voices of critics. The technique is commonly used in persuasive speeches by political candidates to discredit their opponents and to make themselves seem more worthy.<ref>{{cite book |title=The art of creative critical thinking |last=C. S. Kim |first=John |authorlink= |year=1993 |publisher=University Press of America |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=317\u2013318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5PXWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22card+stacking%22&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEgQ6AEwBQ |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe term originates from the [[Magic (illusion)|magician]]'s gimmick of \"[[Glossary of poker terms#cold deck|stacking the deck]]\", which involves presenting a [[Playing card|deck of cards]] that appears to have been randomly shuffled but which is, in fact, 'stacked' in a specific order. The magician knows the order and is able to control the outcome of the trick. In poker, cards can be stacked so that certain hands are dealt to certain players.<ref>{{cite book |title=Clear thinking: a practical introduction |last=Ruchlis |first=Hyman |authorlink= |author2=Sandra Oddo |year=1990 |publisher=Prometheus Books |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=195\u2013196 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04JqAAAAMAAJ&q=%22card+stacking%22&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe phenomenon can be applied to any subject and has wide applications. Whenever a broad spectrum of information exists, appearances can be rigged by highlighting some facts and ignoring others. Card stacking can be a tool of advocacy groups or of those groups with specific agendas.<ref>{{cite book |title=Immunization: the reality behind the myth, Volume 3 |last=James |first=Walene |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=193\u2013194 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQHPoGs6CvIC&pg=PA193&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22card%20stacking%22&f=false |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> For example, an enlistment poster might focus upon an impressive picture, with words such as \"travel\" and \"adventure\", while placing the words, \"enlist for two to four years\" at the bottom in a smaller and less noticeable point size.<ref>{{cite book |title=Techniques of Propaganda and Persuasion |last=Shabo |first=Magedah |authorlink= |year=2008 |publisher=Prestwick House Inc |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=24\u201329 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sDIbJUAZeuwC&pg=PA28&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22card%20stacking%22&f=false |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philosophy}}\n{{columns list|colwidth=22em|<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n* ''[[Ad hoc]]''\n* [[Biased sample]]\n* [[Confirmation bias]]\n* [[Data dredging]]\n* [[False balance]]\n* [[Fact-checking]]\n* [[Hawthorne effect]]\n* [[Jumping to conclusions]]\n* [[Othello error]]\n* [[Pars destruens/pars construens]]\n* [[Proof by example]]\n* [[Prooftext]]\n* [[Quasi-experiment]]\n* [[Quoting out of context]]\n* [[Selection bias]]\n* [[Special pleading]]\n* [[Survivorship bias]]\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Disinformation}}\n{{Informal fallacy}}\n{{Propaganda}}\n\n[[Category:Inductive fallacies]]\n[[Category:Informal fallacies]]\n[[Category:Cognitive inertia]]\n[[Category:Metaphors referring to food and drink]]\n[[Category:Misuse of statistics]]\n[[Category:Public relations techniques]]\n[[Category:Evidence]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|Logical fallacy}}\n'''Cherry picking''', '''suppressing evidence''', or the '''fallacy of incomplete evidence''' is the act of pointing to individual cases or data that seem to confirm a particular position while ignoring a significant portion of related cases or data that may [[Contradiction|contradict]] that position. It is a kind of [[fallacy]] of selective attention, the most common example of which is the [[confirmation bias]].<ref>[http://www.iep.utm.edu/fallacy/#SuppressedEvidence The Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, \"Fallacies\", Bradley Dowden (2010)]</ref><ref>[http://www.logicallyfallacious.com/index.php/logical-fallacies/66-cherry-picking Cherry Picking]</ref> Cherry picking may be committed intentionally or unintentionally. This fallacy is a major problem in public debate.<ref>{{cite web|last= Klass|first= Gary|title= Just Plain Data Analysis: Common Statistical Fallacies in Analyses of Social Indicator Data. Department of Politics and Government, Illinois State University|website= statlit.org. ~2008|accessdate= March 25, 2014|url= http://www.statlit.org/pdf/2008KlassASA.pdf|format= PDF|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140325173711/http://www.statlit.org/pdf/2008KlassASA.pdf|archivedate= March 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe term is based on the perceived process of harvesting fruit, such as [[cherry|cherries]].  The picker would be expected to only select the ripest and healthiest fruits. An observer who only sees the selected fruit may thus wrongly conclude that most, or even all, of the tree's fruit is in a likewise good condition. This can also give a false impression of the quality of the fruit (since it is only a sample and is not a [[representative sample]]). A concept sometimes confused with cherry picking is the idea of gathering only the fruit that is easy to harvest, while ignoring other fruit that is higher up on the tree and thus more difficult to obtain (see [[low-hanging fruit]]).\n\nCherry picking has a negative connotation as the practice neglects, overlooks or directly suppresses evidence that could lead to a complete picture. \n\nCherry picking can be found in many [[fallacy|logical fallacies]]. For example, the \"fallacy of [[anecdotal evidence]]\" tends to overlook large amounts of data in favor of that known personally, \"selective use of evidence\" rejects material unfavorable to an argument, while a [[false dichotomy]] picks only two options when more are available. Cherry picking can refer to the selection of data or data sets so a study or survey will give desired, predictable results which may be misleading or even completely contrary to reality.<ref name=\"Goldacre2008\">{{cite book|last=Goldacre|first=Ben|authorlink=Ben Goldacre|title=Bad Science|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Gv1NQubrGNIC|year=2008|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|isbn=978-0-00-728319-4|pages=97\u201399}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAn anecdotal story about the 5th century BC atheist philosopher [[Diagoras of Melos]] says how, when shown the votive gifts of people who had supposedly escaped death by shipwreck by praying to gods, he pointed out that many people ''had'' died at sea in spite of their prayers, yet these cases were not likewise commemorated.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jennifer Michael|last=Hecht|authorlink=Jennifer Michael Hecht|title=Doubt: A History|publisher=Harper San Francisco|year=2003|chapter=Whatever Happened to Zeus and Hera?, 600 BCE-1 CE|pages=9\u201310|isbn=0-06-009795-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QJb16_AAePkC&pg=PA10}}</ref> [[Michel de Montaigne]] (1533-1592) in his [[Essays (Montaigne)|essay on prophecies]] comments on people willing to believe in the validity of supposed seers: \n{{quote|I see some who are mightily given to study and comment upon their almanacs, and produce them to us as an authority when anything has fallen out pat; and, for that matter, it is hardly possible but that these alleged authorities sometimes stumble upon a truth amongst an infinite number of lies. ... I think never the better of them for some such accidental hit. ... [N]obody records their flimflams and false prognostics, forasmuch as they are infinite and common; but if they chop upon one truth, that carries a mighty report, as being rare, incredible, and prodigious.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michel de Montaigne|title=Essays|chapter=Chapter XI--Of Prognostications|others=Translated by Charles Cotton|year=1877|orig-year=First French edition 1580|url=http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/3600}}</ref>}}\n\n==In science==\n[[File:Temperaturanstieg-vergleich-zwischen-ausschnitt-und-gesamtverlauf.gif|thumb|320px|Cherry-picking is often used in [[denialism|science denial]] such as [[climate change denial]]. For example, by deliberately cherry picking appropriate time periods, here 1998\u20132012, an artificial \"pause\" can be created, even when there is an ongoing warming trend.<ref name=\"Hansson\">[[Sven Ove Hansson]]: ''Science denial as a form of pseudoscience''. [[Studies in History and Philosophy of Science]]. 63, 2017, pp 39\u201347, {{DOI|10.1016/j.shpsa.2017.05.002}}.</ref>]]\n\nCherry picking is one of the epistemological characteristics of [[denialism]] and widely used by different science [[Denialism|denialists]] to seemingly contradict scientific findings. For example, it is used in [[climate change denial]], denial of the negative health effects of consuming [[tobacco products]] and passive smoking and [[evolution denial]] by creationists.<ref name=\"Hansson\" />\n\n{{Quote\n| Choosing to make selective choices among competing evidence, so as to emphasize those results that support a given position, while ignoring or dismissing any findings that do not support it, is a practice known as \"cherry picking\" and is a hallmark of poor science or pseudo-science.<ref name=\"scienceornot\">[http://scienceornot.net/2012/04/03/devious-deception-in-displaying-data-cherry-picking/ \"Devious deception in displaying data: Cherry picking\"], ''Science or Not,'' April 3, 2012, retrieved 16 February 2015</ref>\n| [[Richard Somerville]], Testimony before the US House of Representatives Committee on Energy and Commerce Subcommittee on Energy and Power, March 8, 2011.\n}}\n\n{{Quote\n | Rigorous science looks at all the evidence (rather than cherry picking only favorable evidence), controls for variables as to identify what is actually working, uses blinded observations so as to minimize the effects of bias, and uses internally consistent logic.\"<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.sciencebasedmedicine.org/index.php/a-skeptic-in-oz/\n | title = A Skeptic In Oz\n | last = Novella \n | first = Steven\n | authorlink = Steven Novella\n | date = 26 April 2011\n | website = [[Science-Based Medicine (website)|Science-Based Medicine]]\n | access-date = 16 February 2015 }}\n</ref>\n | [[Steven Novella]], \"A Skeptic In Oz\", April 26, 2011\n}}\n\n==In medicine==\nIn a 2002 study, a review of previous medical data found cherry picking in tests of anti-depression medication:\n\n<blockquote>[researchers] reviewed 31 antidepressant efficacy trials to identify the primary exclusion criteria used in determining eligibility for participation. Their findings suggest that patients in current antidepressant trials represent only a minority of patients treated in routine clinical practice for depression. Excluding potential clinical trial subjects with certain profiles means that the ability to generalize the results of antidepressant efficacy trials lacks empirical support, according to the authors.<ref>{{Cite journal |title=Typical Depression Patients Excluded from Drug Trials; exclusion criteria: is it 'cherry pickin'? |url= |journal=The Brown University Psychopharmacology Update |publisher=Wiley Periodicals |volume=13 |issue=5 |date=May 2002 |pages=1\u20133|issn=1068-5308}} Based on the studies:\n* {{cite journal |last1=Posternak |first1=MA |last2=Zimmerman |first2=M |last3=Keitner |first3=GI |last4=Miller |first4=IW |title=A reevaluation of the exclusion criteria used in antidepressant efficacy trials |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |date=February 2002 |volume=159 |issue=2 |pages=191\u2013200 |pmid=11823258 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.159.2.191}}\n* {{cite journal |last1=Zimmerman |first1=M |last2=Mattia |first2=JI |last3=Posternak |first3=MA |title=Are subjects in pharmacological treatment trials of depression representative of patients in routine clinical practice? |journal=The American Journal of Psychiatry |date=March 2002 |volume=159 |issue=3 |pages=469\u201373 |pmid=11870014 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.159.3.469}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==In argumentation==\nIn argumentation, the practice of \"[[quote mining]]\" is a form of cherry picking,<ref name=\"scienceornot\" /> in which the debater selectively picks some quotes supporting a position (or exaggerating an opposing position) while ignoring those that moderate the original quote or put it into a different context. Cherry picking in debates is a large problem as the facts themselves are true but need to be put in context. Because research cannot be done live and is often untimely, cherry-picked facts or quotes usually stick in the public mainstream and, even when corrected, lead to widespread misrepresentation of groups targeted.\n\n==One-sided argument<!--'One-sided argument' redirects here-->==\nA '''one-sided argument''' (also known as '''card stacking''', '''stacking the deck''', '''ignoring the counterevidence''', '''slanting''', and '''suppressed evidence''')<ref name=stacking>{{cite web|title=One-Sidedness - The Fallacy Files|url=http://www.fallacyfiles.org/onesided.html|accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref> is an [[informal fallacy]] that occurs when only the reasons supporting a proposition are supplied, while all reasons opposing it are omitted.\n\nPhilosophy professor [[Peter Suber]] has written: \"The one-sidedness fallacy does not make an argument invalid. It may not even make the argument unsound. The fallacy consists in persuading readers, and perhaps ourselves, that we have said enough to tilt the scale of evidence and therefore enough to justify a judgment. If we have been one-sided, though, then we haven't yet said enough to justify a judgment. The arguments on the other side may be stronger than our own. We won't know until we examine them.  So the one-sidedness fallacy doesn't mean that your premises are false or irrelevant, only that they are incomplete.\"<ref name=\"Suber\">{{cite web |url=http://www.earlham.edu/~peters/courses/inflogic/onesided.htm |title=The One-Sidedness Fallacy |author=Peter Suber |accessdate=25 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"With rational messages, you need to decide if you want to use a one-sided argument or a two-sided argument. A one-sided argument only presents the pro side of the argument, while a two-sided argument presents both sides. Which one you use will depend on which one meets your needs and the type of audience. Generally, one-sided arguments are better with audiences already favorable to your message. Two-sided arguments are best with audiences who are opposed to your argument, are better educated or have already been exposed to counter arguments.\"<ref name=\"Suber\"/>\n\n'''Card stacking''' is a [[propaganda]] technique that seeks to manipulate audience perception of an issue by emphasizing one side and repressing another.<ref>{{cite book |title=The fine art of propaganda: a study of Father Coughlin's s=Institute for Propaganda Analysis |first= |authorlink= |year=1939 |publisher=Harcourt Brace and Company |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=95\u2013101 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EzVMAAAAIAAJ&q=%22card+stacking%22&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> Such emphasis may be achieved through [[media bias]] or the use of [[One-sided argument|one-sided]] testimonials, or by simply [[Censorship|censoring]] the voices of critics. The technique is commonly used in persuasive speeches by political candidates to discredit their opponents and to make themselves seem more worthy.<ref>{{cite book |title=The art of creative critical thinking |last=C. S. Kim |first=John |authorlink= |year=1993 |publisher=University Press of America |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=317\u2013318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5PXWAAAAMAAJ&q=%22card+stacking%22&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CEgQ6AEwBQ |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe term originates from the [[Magic (illusion)|magician]]'s gimmick of \"[[Glossary of poker terms#cold deck|stacking the deck]]\", which involves presenting a [[Playing card|deck of cards]] that appears to have been randomly shuffled but which is, in fact, 'stacked' in a specific order. The magician knows the order and is able to control the outcome of the trick. In poker, cards can be stacked so that certain hands are dealt to certain players.<ref>{{cite book |title=Clear thinking: a practical introduction |last=Ruchlis |first=Hyman |authorlink= |author2=Sandra Oddo |year=1990 |publisher=Prometheus Books |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=195\u2013196 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04JqAAAAMAAJ&q=%22card+stacking%22&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe phenomenon can be applied to any subject and has wide applications. Whenever a broad spectrum of information exists, appearances can be rigged by highlighting some facts and ignoring others. Card stacking can be a tool of advocacy groups or of those groups with specific agendas.<ref>{{cite book |title=Immunization: the reality behind the myth, Volume 3 |last=James |first=Walene |authorlink= |year=1995 |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=193\u2013194 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EQHPoGs6CvIC&pg=PA193&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEMQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22card%20stacking%22&f=false |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref> For example, an enlistment poster might focus upon an impressive picture, with words such as \"travel\" and \"adventure\", while placing the words, \"enlist for two to four years\" at the bottom in a smaller and less noticeable point size.<ref>{{cite book |title=Techniques of Propaganda and Persuasion |last=Shabo |first=Magedah |authorlink= |year=2008 |publisher=Prestwick House Inc |location= |isbn= |page= |pages=24\u201329 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sDIbJUAZeuwC&pg=PA28&dq=%22card+stacking%22&hl=en&ei=61PtTK63KYOglAe5hpmcAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=%22card%20stacking%22&f=false |accessdate=November 24, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Philosophy}}\n{{columns list|colwidth=22em|<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n* ''[[Ad hoc]]''\n* [[Biased sample]]\n* [[Confirmation bias]]\n* [[Data dredging]]\n* [[False balance]]\n* [[Fact-checking]]\n* [[Hawthorne effect]]\n* [[Jumping to conclusions]]\n* [[Othello error]]\n* [[Pars destruens/pars construens]]\n* [[Proof by example]]\n* [[Prooftext]]\n* [[Quasi-experiment]]\n* [[Quoting out of context]]\n* [[Selection bias]]\n* [[Special pleading]]\n* [[Survivorship bias]]\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Disinformation}}\n{{Informal fallacy}}\n{{Propaganda}}\n\n[[Category:Inductive fallacies]]\n[[Category:Informal fallacies]]\n[[Category:Cognitive inertia]]\n[[Category:Metaphors referring to food and drink]]\n[[Category:Misuse of statistics]]\n[[Category:Public relations techniques]]\n[[Category:Evidence]]\n", "name_user": "Llee99", "label": "safe", "comment": "added similar cases on 1st line. Cherry picking is ignoring significant portion of related and similar cases to emphasise the 'picking'", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cherry_picking"}
{"title_page": "Jim Clash", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| James Michael Clash    =\n| image             =Jim-clash.jpg\n| image_size        =\n| image_caption     =Adventurer Jim Clash speaking at The Explorers Club\n| full_name         =\n| birth_name        = James Michael Clash\n| nickname          =\n| birth_place       =[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| education         =BA English [[University of Maryland]], MBA from [[Columbia University]]\n| known_for         =\n| notable_works     =''Forbes To The Limits'', ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1960s'', ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1970s and 1980s''\n| nationality       =\n| partnerships      =\n| occupation        =Participatory Adventure Journalist, Author\n| awards            =\n| boards            = \n| website           =\n| caption           =Adventurer Jim Clash speaking at The Explorers Club\n}}\n\n'''James Michael \"Jim\" Clash''' is an American participatory adventure journalist and author.<ref name=\"01inspiringfigures\">{{cite web |last1=Gladden |first1=Becca |title=Jim Clash \u2013 Business and Adventure Journalist, Author \u2013 Part One |url=https://www.inspiring-figures.com/single-post/2018/03/28/Jim-Clash-%E2%80%93-Business-and-Adventure-Journalist-Author-%E2%80%93-Part-One |website=Discover Con |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> He has engaged in some of the world\u2019s most daring exploits and lived to write about them.<ref name=\"02inspiringfigures\">{{cite web |last1=Gladden |first1=Becca |title=Jim Clash \u2013 Business and Adventure Journalist, Author \u2013 Part Two |url=https://www.inspiring-figures.com/single-post/2018/04/04/Jim-Clash-%E2%80%93-Business-and-Adventure-Journalist-Author-%E2%80%93-Part-Two |website=Discover Con |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He has written for ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref name=\"03forbescontributor\">{{cite web |title=Contributor Jim Clash |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/#42518f864f17 |website=Forbes |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> [[AskMen]],<ref name=\"16askmen\">{{cite web |last1=Jim |first1=Clash |title=Elon Musk Interview |url=https://www.askmen.com/entertainment/right-stuff/elon-musk-interview.html |website=AskMen |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> ''[[Huffington Post]]'',<ref name=\"08huffpost\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=American Adventurer Tackles Deadly Japanese Blowfish: Survives |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/deadly-japanese-blowfish_n_881986 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref> ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'',<ref name=\"12bloomberg\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Buzz Aldrin, Moonwalker, Says U.S. Must Shoot for Mars |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-05-24/buzz-aldrin-moonwalker-says-u-s-must-shoot-for-mars |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Automobile (magazine)|Automobile]]''.<ref name=\"32automobilemag\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Bugatti Veyron\u2019s Top Speed \u2013 Strap In and Hunker Down |url=https://www.automobilemag.com/news/bugatti-veyrons-top-speed-james-clash/ |website=Automobile Mag |accessdate=17 June 2009}}</ref> He has written three books: ''Forbes To The Limits'',<ref name=\"04amazonforbes\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Forbes To The Limits: Pushing Yourself to the Edge--in Adventure and in Business Hardcover \u2013 April 7, 2003 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Forbes-Limits-Yourself-Edge-Adventure/dp/0471210935/ |website=Amazon |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1960s'',<ref>{{cite web |title=The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1960s |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20426024-the-right-stuff |website=Goodreads |accessdate=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"05amazonright\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1970s and 1980s |url=https://www.amazon.com/Right-Stuff-Interviews-Icons-1970s-ebook/dp/B00AM7O8E0/ |website=Amazon |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> and ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1970s and 1980s''.<ref name=\"05amazonright\" /> Jim is a Fellow and former Board Member of [[The Explorers Club]] and is also ticket holder 610 on [[Virgin Galactic]] for a flight to space.<ref name=\"07usatoday\">{{cite web |last1=DiBlasio |first1=Natalie |title=Space enthusiast not deterred by Virgin crash |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/11/01/virgin-galactic-ticket/18323961/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n\n== Early life ==\n\nJim was born in [[Tokyo, Japan]] and raised in [[Laurel, Maryland]].<ref name=\"08huffpost\" /> He has a Bachelor of Arts degree in English from the [[University of Maryland]], and an MBA from [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\">{{cite web |title=Mountain Stories 2011 |url=https://explorers.org/about/mountain_stories_2011 |website=The Explorers Club |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Jim's first foray into adventure began as an amateur \"ham\" radio operator.<ref name=\"10forbes2\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=There's magic in it |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1997/0707/6001438a.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=7 July 2001}}</ref> Prior to becoming an adventure journalist, Jim covered mutual funds and finance for [[Forbes]] magazine, and was an account director in the advertising industry.\n\n== Interviews with iconic figures ==\n\nAs an adventure journalist, Jim has interviewed 8 of the 12 moon walkers<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=What's It Like To Stand On The Lunar Surface? Seven Moonwalkers Give Us The Straight Dope |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/11/21/whats-it-like-to-stand-on-the-lunar-surface-six-moonwalkers-give-us-the-straight-dope/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Moonwalker Harrison Schmitt Discusses The Significance Of This Year's 50th Anniversary Of Apollo 11 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2019/03/10/moonwalker-harrison-schmitt-discusses-the-significance-of-this-years-50th-anniversary-of-apollo-11/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref> including [[Neil Armstrong]]<ref name=\"11ohio\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=James M. Clash: Selfless hero of a bygone age |url=https://www.ohio.com/article/20120829/OPINION/308299076 |website=Ohio.com |accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and [[Buzz Aldrin]].<ref name=\"12bloomberg\" /> Jim has also interviewed legendary aviation pioneers including [[Chuck Yeager]],<ref name=\"13chuckyeager\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Chuck Yeager: 'Right Stuff' Character Was Right-On |url=http://www.chuckyeager.org/news/chuck-yeager-right-stuff-character-was-right-on/ |website=Chuck Yeager |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Senator John Glenn,<ref name=\"14forbes3\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Senator John Glenn Tribute: The Late Great Space Hero In His Own Words |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/12/09/senator-john-glenn-the-late-great-space-hero-in-his-own-words/#75abf94d7c1e |website=Forbes |accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> Sir Richard Branson,<ref name=\"15youtube\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Jim Clash Chats w/ Richard Branson, Burt Rutan, Brian Binnie |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Expu8HsQIvQ&feature=youtu.be |website=YouTube |accessdate=15 February 2008}}</ref> [[Elon Musk]],<ref name=\"16askmen\" /> [[Jeff Bezos]],<ref name=\"17inaskmen\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Jeff Bezos Interview |url=https://in.askmen.com/the-right-stuff/1091242/article/jeff-bezos-interview |website=AskMen |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Alan Eustace,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Long-Time Google Executive Alan Eustace On His 135,890-Ft. World Record Parachute Jump |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/11/11/humble-google-exec-alan-eustace-on-his-135890-ft-parachute-jump-world-record/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref> Bertrand Piccard,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Bertrand Piccard Wins Explorers Medal For World Record Balloon and Solar-Powered Flights |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/01/28/bertrand-piccard-wins-explorers-medal-for-world-record-balloon-and-solar-powered-flights/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=28 January 2017}}</ref> Joe Kittinger,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Meet Joe Kittinger, The First Man To Kiss The Sky |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/03/23/meet-joe-kittinger-the-first-man-to-kiss-the-sky/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=23 March 2017}}</ref> and Felix Baumgartner.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Four Questions for Felix Baumgartner Five Years After His Amazing 128,100-Foot Parachute Jump |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/10/18/four-questions-for-felix-baumgartner-five-years-after-his-amazing-128100-foot-parachute-jump/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=18 October 2017}}</ref> Notable mountaineers include Sir Edmund Hillary,<ref name=\"18forbes4\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=In A World Lacking Character, Sir Edmund Hillary Had It In Spades |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/01/30/in-a-world-lacking-character-sir-edmund-hillary-had-it-in-spades/#3ab0391633ae |website=Forbes |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> Reinhold Messner,<ref name=\"19askmen2\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Reinhold Messner Interview |url=https://www.askmen.com/entertainment/right-stuff/reinhold-messner-interview.html |website=AskMen |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Sir Chris Bonington,<ref name=\"20forbes5\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Mountaineering Legend Chris Bonington: Sir'd, But Never Shaken |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2015/04/09/mountaineering-legend-chris-bonington-sird-but-never-shaken/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref> Jamling Tenzing Norgay,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Jamling Tenzing Norgay Interview |url=https://www.askmen.com/entertainment/right-stuff/jamling-tenzing-norgay-interview.html |website=Ask Men |accessdate=22 March 2019}}</ref> and Jim Whittaker.<ref name=\"21bloomberg2\">{{cite web |title=Mount Everest\u2019s First U.S. Conqueror Recalls 1963 Climb |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-04-18/mount-everest-s-first-u-s-conqueror-recalls-1963-climb |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nJim has also interviewed deep ocean explorers Don Walsh<ref name=\"22forbes6\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=What Does The Deepest Point On The Planet Look Like? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/05/04/what-does-the-deepest-point-on-the-planet-look-like/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=4 May 2017}}</ref> and [[James Cameron]]<ref name=\"23vimeo\">{{cite web |title=Exploring Legends Interview Series feat. James Cameron |url=https://vimeo.com/101025877 |website=Vimeo |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> as well as notable race car drivers Sir Jackie Stewart<ref name=\"24forbes7\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Formula One Legend Sir Jackie Stewart On Dyslexia, Being Bullied and More |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/08/25/dyslexic-formula-one-legend-sir-jackie-stewart-on-being-bullied-more/#42a733405b23 |website=Forbes |accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref> and [[Mario Andretti]]<ref name=\"25forbes8\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=What Does Mario Andretti Think About Racing? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2019/01/31/five-questions-for-mario-andretti/#1098752761a1 |website=Forbes |accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref> and famous musicians Roger Daltrey,<ref name=\"26forbes9\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=The Who's Roger Daltrey On Teenage Cancer Crisis In America |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2015/02/08/the-whos-roger-daltrey-on-teenage-cancer-crisis-in-america/#64895af06176 |website=Forbes |accessdate=8 February 2015}}</ref> Pete Townshend,<ref name=\"27forbes10\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Interview: The Who's Pete Townshend On What Teen Cancer Means To Him |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/03/20/interview-the-whos-pete-townshend-on-what-teen-cancer-means-to-him/#4c9a50363df3 |website=Forbes |accessdate=20 March 2016}}</ref> Grace Slick,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Grace Slick: 'Rock Is Like Sports - You Have A Certain Run, Then Get Out' |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2015/12/11/grace-slick-rock-is-like-sports-you-have-a-certain-run-then-get-out/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref> [[Ginger Baker]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Ginger Baker On Firing Jack Bruce, The Origins Of Cream |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2015/06/16/ginger-baker-on-firing-jack-bruce-origins-of-cream/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref> and [[Art Garfunkel]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Garfunkel On Relationship With Simon: 'Love' And 'Like Weather In Slow Motion' |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2014/11/29/garfunkel-on-relationship-with-simon-love-and-like-weather-in-slow-motion/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> Jim\u2019s interviews are as diverse as Sir Roger Bannister,<ref name=\"28huffpost2\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Sir Roger Bannister On The Olympics And Oxford's Runners |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/roger-bannister-olympics-oxford_n_1716258 |website=Huffpost |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref> Dr. Edward Teller,<ref name=\"29forbes11\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Was Edward Teller Really The Nuclear Hawk He Was Made Out To Be? |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/05/08/was-edward-teller-really-the-nuclear-hawk-he-was-made-out-to-be/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref> [[Joe Frazier]],<ref name=\"30youtube2\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Jim Clash Interviews Smokin' Joe Frazier (Part 1) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S8hVIHJffyU&feature=youtu.be |website=Youtube |accessdate=12 July 2007}}</ref> Mikhail Baryshnikov,<ref name=\"31forbes12\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Interview: Mikhail Baryshnikov Looks Back On A Decade With His NYC Arts Center |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2015/12/15/interview-mikhail-baryshnikov-looks-back-on-a-decade-with-his-nyc-arts-center/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=15 December 2015}}</ref> and Neil de Grasse Tyson.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Neil deGrasse Tyson Interview Neil deGrasse Tyson On Time Travel, Mars & Making Science Easy |url=https://www.askmen.com/entertainment/right-stuff/neil-degrasse-tyson-interview.html |website=Ask Men |accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Participatory adventure journalism ==\n\n=== Aircraft ===\n\n* Flown in a MiG-25 Foxbat to 84,000 feet above [[Russia]] at Mach 2.6.<ref name=\"37forbes15\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Joining The 16-Mile High Club |url=https://www.forbes.com/2003/04/22/cz_jc_0422feat.html#75bdeec77180 |website=Forbes |accessdate=22 April 2003}}</ref>\n* Supersonic speeds in an English Electric Lighting and the Concorde.<ref name=\"38huffpost3\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Supersonic Flight Catastrophe in South Africa, One Year Later |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/supersonic-flights-fraugh_n_783346 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref>\n* Weightlessness parabolic flights in an Ilyushin-76.<ref name=\"39popularmechanics\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=I Am Paying $200,000 for Five Minutes in Space |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/space/rockets/a24264/virgin-galactic-astronaut/ |website=Popular Mechanics |accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n* Flown in formation with the Breitling Jet Team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Breitling Jet Team - What It's Really Like To Fly With The World's Wildest Pilots, The Breitling Jet Team |url=https://in.askmen.com/experience/1106498/article/breitling-jet-team |website=Ask Men |accessdate=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n* Aerobatic flight with [[Red Bull]] Race Team in [[Indianapolis]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Over, Under, Sideways, Down: Red Bull Air Race Ride-Along Thrills, Impresses |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/10/17/over-under-sideways-down-red-bull-air-races-thrill-impress/#269482ac64be |website=Forbes |accessdate=17 October 2017}}</ref>\n* Trained for upcoming [[Virgin Galactic]] flight in a centrifuge up to 6 Gs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=The G Spot For Space Tourists |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/01/01/the-g-spot-for-space-tourists/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=1 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Autos===\n\nJim has driven several cars over 200&nbsp;mph including:\n* A [[Bugatti]] Veyron at a top speed of 253.2&nbsp;mph.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Bugatti Veyron\u2019s Top Speed \u2013 Strap In and Hunker Down |url=https://www.automobilemag.com/news/bugatti-veyrons-top-speed-james-clash/ |website=Automobile |accessdate=17 June 2009}}</ref>\n* Other 200-mph drives include Porsches, Ferraris, Lamborghinis, Bentleys, McLarens and Corvettes.<ref name=\"33forbes12\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Confessions Of A Speed Freak: Life At 200 MPH In Bugattis, Bentleys, Lamborghinis And Porsches |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2015/11/10/confessions-of-a-speed-freak-life-at-200-mph-in-bugattis-bentleys-lamborghinis-and-porsches/#61b78c7434fc |website=Forbes |accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n* An IndyCar at an average lap speed of over 200&nbsp;mph at Texas Motor Speedway.<ref name=\"34askmen3\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Driving 200 Mph In An Indy Car |url=https://www.askmen.com/entertainment/right-stuff/driving-200-mph-in-an-indycar.html |website=AskMen |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n* Graduate of Frank Hawley Drag Racing School.<ref name=\"35forbes13\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Drive It Like You Stole It: Drag Racing Lessons Are Not For The Faint Of Heart |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/07/19/drive-it-like-you-stole-it-drag-racing-lessons-are-not-for-the-faint-of-heart/#1ab94f78220d |website=Forbes |accessdate=19 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Drove with [[Mario Andretti]] at 200&nbsp;mph at Indianapolis Motor Speedway.<ref name=\"36forbes14\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Life in the Fastest Lane: Race Down the Indianapolis Motor Speedway at 200mph with Mario Andretti |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/07/06/racing-indianapolis-motor-speedway-mario-andretti/#44b9fc727e50 |website=Forbes |accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n* Reported from start line while 11,000-hp nitro-methane dragsters blasted off to 330&nbsp;mph in less than four seconds.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=NHRA Fans Love The Smell Of Nitro-Methane In The Morning |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2018/05/01/nhra-fans-love-the-smell-of-nitro-methane-in-the-morning/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=1 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Drove off-road Baja 1000 vehicles in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Shaken, Not Stirred: Pounding Baja's Off-Road Desert Dust |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/07/27/shaken-not-stirred-pounding-bajas-off-road-desert-dust/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=27 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Drove a tank over a car.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Want To Crush Cars With A Tank? You Can Do It With This Minnesota Outfit |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/06/29/want-to-crush-a-car-with-a-60-ton-tank-a-minnesota-outfit-will-let-you-do-it-for-a-price/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Tested at Bonneville Salt Flats<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Blowing Salt at Bonneville |url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2005/0425/058.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=25 April 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Military===\n\n* Rode a B-52 bomber with The U.S. Air Force in Minot, [[North Dakota]].<ref name=\"46forbes18\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Ever Want To Fly An Old B-52 Bomber? Read This First-Person Account |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/10/02/ever-fly-in-an-old-b-52-bomber-as-a-civillian-read-this-first-person-acount/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=2 October 2017}}</ref>\n* Flew in a T-38 and suited up in a U-2 Space suit, Beale AFB, [[California]].<ref name=\"47forbes19\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Scuse Me While I Kiss The Sky: What It's Like To Fly In A Supersonic T-38 Talon |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2018/06/15/scuse-me-while-i-kiss-the-sky/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=15 June 2018}}</ref>\n* Embedded with U.S. Army 82nd Airborne, Fort Bragg, [[North Carolina]].<ref name=\"48forbes20\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Intrepid Reporter Embeds With Army's 82nd Airborne, Ft. Bragg |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2018/05/11/intrepid-reporter-embeds-with-armys-82nd-airborne-ft-bragg/#df4bfdc465ed |website=Forbes |accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref>\n* Flew supersonic in an F-15 fighter jet at Seymour Johnson AFB, [[North Carolina]].<ref name=\"49forbes21\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=What's It Like To Go Supersonic In An F-15E Fighter Jet? Read On |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/08/17/what-is-it-like-to-go-supersonic-in-an-f-15e-fighter-jet-read-on/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref>\n* Reported from nuclear missile bunker in Minot, [[North Dakota]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Visit A Live USAF Nuclear Missile Bunker 70 Feet Below Minot, ND |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/09/29/a-first-person-visit-to-a-nuclear-missile-silo-70-feet-below-minot-nd/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n* Reported from Thule AFB in northern [[Greenland]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=While You Sleep, Thule Listens, Watches, Waits |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2019/01/27/while-you-sleep-thule-listens-watches-waits/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n* Reported U.S. Air Force launch from Cape Canaveral, Florida<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Air Force/ULA Rocket Launch Provides Thrills, Chills But No Spills |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2019/03/18/air-forceula-rocket-launch-provides-thrills-chills-but-no-spills/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mountains===\n\nSummited the following mountains:\n* [[Aconcagua]], [[Argentina]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* The [[Matterhorn]], [[Switzerland]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* [[Mont Blanc]], [[France]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* [[Kilimanjaro]], [[Tanzania]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* [[Grand Teton]], [[Wyoming]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* [[Orizaba]] and [[Popocateptl]], [[Mexico]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* [[Cotapaxi]] and [[Cayambe (volcano)|Cayambe]], [[Ecuador]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* Virgin Peaks in [[Antarctica]] and [[Greenland]]<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n* [[Mount Fuji]], [[Japan]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Sacred Mountain |url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2006/1127/074.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=17 November 2006}}</ref>\n* [[Kosciuszko]], [[Australia]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=The puny peak |url=https://www.forbes.com/global/1998/0810/0109080a.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===North and South Poles===\n\n* Skied the last degree (111&nbsp;km) to [[South Pole]].<ref name=\"41nbcnews\">{{cite web |title=South Pole Trek: SKiing to the Nth Degree |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/13481351/ns/travel-active_travel/t/south-pole-trek-skiing-nth-degree/ |website=NBC News |accessdate=25 July 2006}}</ref>\n* Reported from the [[North Pole]] and took the polar plunge.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Swimming with Santa |url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2000/1225/0326142a.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n* Visited high arctic outposts including [[Franz Josef Land]], [[Novaya Zemlya]], [[Wrangel Island]], [[Svalbard]], S'redny Island.<ref name=\"42startalk\">{{cite web |last1=Mullen |first1=Ian |title=Go to Extremes with Chuck Nice, Gary O'Reilly, Adventure Journalist Jim Clash and more |url=https://www.startalkradio.net/go-to-extremes-with-chuck-nice-gary-oreilly-adventure-journalist-jim-clash-and-more/ |website=Star Talk Radio |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Oceans===\n\n* Participated in America\u2019s Cup Land Rover BAR race.<ref name=\"43forbes15\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Participatory Adventure: Sixth-Man Crew Duties Thrill At America's Cup NYC Race |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/05/08/participatory-adventure-sixth-man-crew-duties-thrill-at-americas-cup-nyc-race/#353bf08a1f77 |website=Forbes |accessdate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n* Rode in Triton submersible to 1,000 feet below the Atlantic Ocean.<ref name=\"44forbes16\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Nekton Deep-Ocean Science: 1,000 Feet Below the Atlantic's Surface |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/07/30/nekton-deep-ocean-science-thrills-writer-1000-feet-below-atlantics-surface/#acdcdfc3cafb |website=Forbes |accessdate=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n* Drove a Superboat at 140&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"45forbes17\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Liquid Speed |url=https://www.forbes.com/2006/10/25/speed-boat-racing-forbeslife-sport-cz_jc_1027superboat.html|website=Forbes |accessdate=27 October 2006}}</ref>\n* Jet-skied with surfing champion [[Ken Bradshaw]] in 35-foot waves off Hawaii\u2019s North Shore.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=North Shore Surf Makes for Thrills and Spills in Hawaii |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/monster-north-shore-waves_n_5518779 |website=Huffpost |accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n\n* Stand-in bullfighter for PBR (Professional Bull Riders).<ref name=\"50pagesix\">{{cite web |last1=Mohr |first1=Ian |title=Explorers Club director to speak on bullfighting, Hemingway |url=https://pagesix.com/2014/04/16/explorers-club-director-to-speak-on-hemingway-space-travel/ |website=Page Six |accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref>\n* Bobsledded with the U.S. Olympic Team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Bobsleds Away! |url=https://www.forbes.com/free_forbes/2007/0903/149.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=3 September 2007}}</ref>\n* Tested bullet-proof jacket getting shot point blank with a .38 caliber.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Bulletproof Clothing |url=https://me.askmen.com/apparel/1089069/article/bulletproof-clothing |website=Ask Men |accessdate=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n* Highest, longest rappel in the world at 367 feet.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=South Africa's 367-Foot Record Rappel Provides Big Adrenaline Jolt, Views |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2014/12/22/south-africas-367-foot-record-rappel-provides-big-adrenaline-jolt-views/#38f1493440e9 |website=Forbes |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n* Figure-skated with Olympic Silver Medalist Sasha Cohen.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gladden |first1=Becca |title=Jim Clash - Business and Adventure Journalist, Author - Part One |url=https://www.inspiring-figures.com/single-post/2018/03/28/Jim-Clash-%E2%80%93-Business-and-Adventure-Journalist-Author-%E2%80%93-Part-One |website=Inspiring Figures |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"51forbes22\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=South Africa's 367-Foot Record Rappel Provides Big Adrenaline Jolt, Views |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2014/12/22/south-africas-367-foot-record-rappel-provides-big-adrenaline-jolt-views/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/ Contributor Page on Forbes]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clash, Jim}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from New York City]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Sportswriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Explorers Club]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| James Michael Clash    =\n| image             =Jim-clash.jpg\n| image_size        =\n| image_caption     =Adventurer Jim Clash speaking at The Explorers Club\n| full_name         =\n| birth_name        = James Michael Clash\n| nickname          =\n| birth_place       =[[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| education         =BA English [[University of Maryland]], MBA from [[Columbia University]]\n| known_for         =\n| notable_works     =''Forbes To The Limits'', ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1960s'', ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1970s and 1980s''\n| nationality       =\n| partnerships      =\n| occupation        =Participatory Adventure Journalist, Author\n| awards            =\n| boards            = \n| website           =\n| caption           =Adventurer Jim Clash speaking at The Explorers Club\n}}\n\n'''James Michael \"Jim\" Clash''' is an American participatory adventure journalist and author.<ref name=\"01inspiringfigures\">{{cite web |last1=Gladden |first1=Becca |title=Jim Clash \u2013 Business and Adventure Journalist, Author \u2013 Part One |url=https://www.inspiring-figures.com/single-post/2018/03/28/Jim-Clash-%E2%80%93-Business-and-Adventure-Journalist-Author-%E2%80%93-Part-One |website=Discover Con |accessdate=3 April 2018}}</ref> He has engaged in some of the world\u2019s most daring exploits and lived to write about them.<ref name=\"02inspiringfigures\">{{cite web |last1=Gladden |first1=Becca |title=Jim Clash \u2013 Business and Adventure Journalist, Author \u2013 Part Two |url=https://www.inspiring-figures.com/single-post/2018/04/04/Jim-Clash-%E2%80%93-Business-and-Adventure-Journalist-Author-%E2%80%93-Part-Two |website=Discover Con |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He has written for ''[[Forbes]]'',<ref name=\"03forbescontributor\">{{cite web |title=Contributor Jim Clash |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/#42518f864f17 |website=Forbes |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> [[AskMen]],<ref name=\"16askmen\">{{cite web |last1=Jim |first1=Clash |title=Elon Musk Interview |url=https://www.askmen.com/entertainment/right-stuff/elon-musk-interview.html |website=AskMen |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> ''[[Huffington Post]]'',<ref name=\"08huffpost\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=American Adventurer Tackles Deadly Japanese Blowfish: Survives |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/deadly-japanese-blowfish_n_881986 |website=Huffington Post |accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref> ''[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]'',<ref name=\"12bloomberg\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Buzz Aldrin, Moonwalker, Says U.S. Must Shoot for Mars |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2013-05-24/buzz-aldrin-moonwalker-says-u-s-must-shoot-for-mars |website=Bloomberg |accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> and ''[[Automobile (magazine)|Automobile]]''.<ref name=\"32automobilemag\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Bugatti Veyron\u2019s Top Speed \u2013 Strap In and Hunker Down |url=https://www.automobilemag.com/news/bugatti-veyrons-top-speed-james-clash/ |website=Automobile Mag |accessdate=17 June 2009}}</ref> He has written three books: ''Forbes To The Limits'',<ref name=\"04amazonforbes\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=Forbes To The Limits: Pushing Yourself to the Edge--in Adventure and in Business Hardcover \u2013 April 7, 2003 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Forbes-Limits-Yourself-Edge-Adventure/dp/0471210935/ |website=Amazon |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1960s'',<ref>{{cite web |title=The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1960s |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20426024-the-right-stuff |website=Goodreads |accessdate=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"05amazonright\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1970s and 1980s |url=https://www.amazon.com/Right-Stuff-Interviews-Icons-1970s-ebook/dp/B00AM7O8E0/ |website=Amazon |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> and ''The Right Stuff: Interviews with Icons of the 1970s and 1980s''.<ref name=\"05amazonright\" /> Jim is a Fellow and former Board Member of [[The Explorers Club]] and is also ticket holder 610 on [[Virgin Galactic]] for a flight to space.<ref name=\"07usatoday\">{{cite web |last1=DiBlasio |first1=Natalie |title=Space enthusiast not deterred by Virgin crash |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/11/01/virgin-galactic-ticket/18323961/ |website=USA Today |accessdate=1 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\" />\n\n== Early life ==\n\nJim was born in [[Tokyo, Japan]] and raised in [[Laurel, Maryland]].<ref name=\"08huffpost\" /> He has a Bachelor of Arts degree in English from the [[University of Maryland]], and an MBA from [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"09theexplorersclub\">{{cite web |title=Mountain Stories 2011 |url=https://explorers.org/about/mountain_stories_2011 |website=The Explorers Club |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Jim's first foray into adventure began as an amateur \"ham\" radio operator.<ref name=\"10forbes2\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=There's magic in it |url=https://www.forbes.com/forbes/1997/0707/6001438a.html |website=Forbes |accessdate=7 July 2001}}</ref> Prior to becoming an adventure journalist, Jim covered mutual funds and finance for [[Forbes]] magazine, and was an account director in the advertising industry.\n\n== Interviews with iconic figures ==\n\nAs an adventure journalist, Jim has interviewed 8 of the 12 moon walkers<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=What's It Like To Stand On The Lunar Surface? Seven Moonwalkers Give Us The Straight Dope |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2017/11/21/whats-it-like-to-stand-on-the-lunar-surface-six-moonwalkers-give-us-the-straight-dope/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=21 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Moonwalker Harrison Schmitt Discusses The Significance Of This Year's 50th Anniversary Of Apollo 11 |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2019/03/10/moonwalker-harrison-schmitt-discusses-the-significance-of-this-years-50th-anniversary-of-apollo-11/ |website=Forbes |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref> including [[Neil Armstrong]]<ref name=\"11ohio\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=James |title=James M. Clash: Selfless hero of a bygone age |url=https://www.ohio.com/article/20120829/OPINION/308299076 |website=Ohio.com |accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> and [[Buzz Aldrin]].<ref name=\"12bloomberg\" /> Jim has also interviewed legendary aviation pioneers including [[Chuck Yeager]],<ref name=\"13chuckyeager\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Chuck Yeager: 'Right Stuff' Character Was Right-On |url=http://www.chuckyeager.org/news/chuck-yeager-right-stuff-character-was-right-on/ |website=Chuck Yeager |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> Senator John Glenn,<ref name=\"14forbes3\">{{cite web |last1=Clash |first1=Jim |title=Senator John Glenn Tribute: The Late Great Space Hero In His Own Words |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jimclash/2016/12/09/senator-john-glenn-the-late-great-space-hero-in-his-own-words/#75abf94d7c1e |website=Forbes |accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref> Sir Richard Branson,<ref nam